# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proteomics-bio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] An **isotope-coded affinity tag** (**ICAT**) is an *in-vitro* isotopic labeling method used for quantitative proteomics by mass spectrometry that uses chemical labeling reagents.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] These chemical probes consist of three elements: a reactive group for labeling an amino acid side chain (e.g., iodoacetamide to modify cysteine residues), an isotopically coded linker, and a tag (e.g., biotin) for the affinity isolation of labeled proteins/peptides.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] The samples are combined and then separated through chromatography, then sent through a mass spectrometer to determine the mass-to-charge ratio between the proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] Only cysteine containing peptides can be analysed.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] Since only cysteine containing peptides are analysed, often the post translational modification is lost.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] The original tags were developed using deuterium, but later the same group redesigned the tags using 13C instead to circumvent issues of peak separation during liquid chromatography due to the deuterium interacting with the stationary phase of the column.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] For the quantitative comparison of two proteomes, one sample is labeled with the isotopically light (d0) probe and the other with the isotopically heavy (d8) version.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] To minimize error, both samples are then combined, digested with a protease (i.e., trypsin), and subjected to avidin affinity chromatography to isolate peptides labeled with isotope-coded tagging reagents.
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] These peptides are then analyzed by liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC-MS).
[src:proteomics-bio/isotope-coded-affinity-tag] The ratios of signal intensities of differentially mass-tagged peptide pairs are quantified to determine the relative levels of proteins in the two samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a typical MS procedure, a sample, which may be solid, liquid, or gaseous, is ionized, for example by bombarding it with a beam of electrons.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This may cause some of the sample's molecules to break up into positively charged fragments or simply become positively charged without fragmenting.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] These ions (fragments) are then separated according to their mass-to-charge ratio, for example by accelerating them and subjecting them to an electric or magnetic field: ions of the same mass-to-charge ratio will undergo the same amount of deflection.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions are detected by a mechanism capable of detecting charged particles, such as an electron multiplier.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Results are displayed as spectra of the signal intensity of detected ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The atoms or molecules in the sample can be identified by correlating known masses (e.g. an entire molecule) to the identified masses or through a characteristic fragmentation pattern.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1886, Eugen Goldstein observed rays in gas discharges under low pressure that traveled away from the anode and through channels in a perforated cathode, opposite to the direction of negatively charged cathode rays (which travel from cathode to anode).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Goldstein called these positively charged anode rays "Kanalstrahlen"; the standard translation of this term into English is "canal rays".
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wilhelm Wien found that strong electric or magnetic fields deflected the canal rays and, in 1899, constructed a device with perpendicular electric and magnetic fields that separated the positive rays according to their charge-to-mass ratio (*Q/m*).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wien found that the charge-to-mass ratio depended on the nature of the gas in the discharge tube.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thomson later improved on the work of Wien by reducing the pressure to create the mass spectrograph.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The word *spectrograph* had become part of the international scientific vocabulary by 1884.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Early *spectrometry* devices that measured the mass-to-charge ratio of ions were called *mass spectrographs* which consisted of instruments that recorded a spectrum of mass values on a photographic plate.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A *mass spectroscope* is similar to a *mass spectrograph* except that the beam of ions is directed onto a phosphor screen.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectroscope configuration was used in early instruments when it was desired that the effects of adjustments be quickly observed.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Once the instrument was properly adjusted, a photographic plate was inserted and exposed.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The term mass spectroscope continued to be used even though the direct illumination of a phosphor screen was replaced by indirect measurements with an oscilloscope.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The use of the term *mass spectroscopy* is now discouraged due to the possibility of confusion with light spectroscopy.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectrometry is often abbreviated as *mass-spec* or simply as *MS*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Modern techniques of mass spectrometry were devised by Arthur Jeffrey Dempster and F.W.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sector mass spectrometers known as calutrons were developed by Ernest O.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lawrence and used for separating the isotopes of uranium during the Manhattan Project.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Calutron mass spectrometers were used for uranium enrichment at the Oak Ridge, Tennessee Y-12 plant established during World War II.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1989, half of the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Hans Dehmelt and Wolfgang Paul for the development of the ion trap technique in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 2002, the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to John Bennett Fenn for the development of electrospray ionization (ESI) and Koichi Tanaka for the development of soft laser desorption and their application to the ionization of biological macromolecules, especially proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectrometer consists of 5 components: **sample inlet**, **ion source** (or **ionizer**), **mass analyzer**, **detector**, data system.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each component can be varied somewhat independently from the other components, and the full mass spectrometer itself can be included as a component in an analysis pipeline, allowing great flexibility.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet prepares the sample to be analyzed in a suitable state.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source takes samples from the sample inlet, converts a portion of the sample into a stream of ions, and outputs it to the mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There is a wide variety of ionization techniques, depending on the phase (solid, liquid, gas) of the sample and the efficiency of various ionization mechanisms for the unknown species.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] An extraction system removes ions from the sample, which are then targeted into the mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The mass analyzer takes an input stream of ions and separates ("analyzes") its constituent ions according to their *m/z*, the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector measures the value of an indicator quantity and thus provides data for calculating the abundances of each ion present.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some detectors also give spatial information, e.g., a multichannel plate.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The following describes the operation of a simple mass spectrometer that uses sector type.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consider a sample of sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In the ion source, the sample is vaporized (turned into gas) and ionized (transformed into electrically charged particles) into sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sodium atoms and ions are monoisotopic, with a mass of about 23 daltons (symbol: Da or older symbol: u).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Chloride atoms and ions come in two stable isotopes with masses of approximately 35 u (at a natural abundance of about 75 percent) and approximately 37 u (at a natural abundance of about 25 percent).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyzer part of the spectrometer contains electric and magnetic fields, which exert forces on ions traveling through these fields.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The speed of a charged particle may be increased or decreased while passing through the electric field, and its direction may be altered by the magnetic field.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The magnitude of the deflection of the moving ion's trajectory depends on its mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lighter ions are deflected by the magnetic force to a greater degree than heavier ions (based on Newton's second law of motion, *F* = *ma*).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The streams of magnetically sorted ions pass from the analyzer to the detector, which records the relative abundance of each ion type.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This information is used to determine the chemical element composition of the original sample (i.e. that both sodium and chlorine are present in the sample) and the isotopic composition of its constituents (the ratio of 35Cl to 37Cl).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet provides a stream of neutral molecules, so that the ion source can ionize them.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The classical design produces the stream of molecules in the form of a low-pressure gas.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is low-pressure, so that molecules within the stream does not frequently collide with each other.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions must travel without frequent collisions, because the instrument separates ions by their motion in electric and magnetic fields.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Despite being low-pressure, the sample stream is still at a much higher pressure than the rest of the system, which is held in a greater vacuum.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the sample stream can only enter the ion source chamber via a small pinhole, called a **molecular leak**.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample itself is already a gas, then the sample inlet can simply be a gas inlet with pressure valve.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is a volatile liquid or solid, then it can simply be placed in a chamber, vacuum-pumped to a low pressure.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is not sufficiently volatile, the sample inlet can be fitted within an oven.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is too nonvolatile to be turned into a low-pressure gas, then one can use a **direct probe**.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The direct probe is a probe with a tip of thin wire loop, pin, or a capillary tube.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe is inserted through a vacuum lock into the ionization chamber, so that the tip is close to the ion source.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe can be heated to increase vapor pressure further.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such a system is effective for samples with vapor pressures lower than $10^{-9}$ mmHg at room temperature.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample can be prepared by an earlier analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, it can simply be the gaseous output of a gas chromatography machine as in GC-MS, or the liquid output of a high-performance liquid chromatography machine, as in HPLC-MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The recently developed "atmospheric pressure ionization" techniques allow us to entirely dispense with the sample inlet.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source is the part of the mass spectrometer that transforms the sample from the sample inlet into a stream of ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques with various dimensions for tradeoffs between different choices of ion sources, in terms of monetary cost, accuracy, precision, compatibility with other stages of spectroscopy, ease of use, etc.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, EI is not suitable for coupling to HPLC, i.e.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] LC-MS, since at atmospheric pressure, the filaments used to generate electrons burn out rapidly.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus EI is coupled predominantly with GC, i.e.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] GC-MS, where the entire system is under high vacuum.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two techniques often used with liquid and solid biological samples include electrospray ionization (invented by John Fenn) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI, initially developed as a similar technique Soft Laser Desorption) by K.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tanaka for which a Nobel Prize was awarded and as MALDI by M.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Hard ionization techniques are those that impart high quantities of residual internal energy in the subject molecule, even after ionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Part of the energy would be dissipated by rupturing chemical bonds within the ion, producing many fragmentary radical ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The resultant ions tend to have *m/z* lower than the molecular ion (other than in the case of proton transfer and not including isotope peaks).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common example of hard ionization is electron ionization (EI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The radical ions produced after the first ionization are called second-generation product ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The products are then directed towards the mass analyzer by a repeller electrode.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ionization process often follows predictable cleavage reactions that give rise to fragment ions which, following detection and signal processing, convey structural information about the analyte.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conversely, soft ionization techniques are those that impart little residual energy onto the subject molecule and as such result in little fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Examples include fast atom bombardment (FAB), chemical ionization (CI), atmospheric-pressure chemical ionization (APCI), atmospheric-pressure photoionization (APPI), electrospray ionization (ESI), desorption electrospray ionization (DESI), and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In electron ionization (EI), energetic electrons are produced by a hot cathode: a wire filament heated by running electric current through it, producing energetic electrons by thermionic emission.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrons are then accelerated towards an anode.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The voltage difference between the cathode and the anode determines the energy of the electron stream.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Most organic compounds have ionization energy 8-15 eV, but empirically, the efficiency of ionization is too low unless the electron beam has an energy of 50-70 eV per electron.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The spectral features, including fragmentation patterns, depend on the energy setting.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conventionally for EI, the electron energy is standardized to be exactly 70 eV.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, if one wishes to compare their EI-MS results against standard databases, or produce results that can be added to standard databases, one must standardize their EI electron energy to 70 eV.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI accepts as input a stream of gas from the molecular leak.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The gas stream crosses the electron stream perpendicularly.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion stream then is accerelated by a succession of electrodes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically an ion carrying 1 e would be accelerated to 1-10 keV.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI has many benefits for routine mass spectrometry of small organic molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is cheap and robust, with reproducible spectrograms.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Databases for EI spectrograms are widely available and covers many such molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI is unsuited for large molecules, such as most biomolecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a hard technique, which tends to break down large molecule ions during flight, since large molecules are particularly easy to fragment.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Furthermore, large molecules are hard to volatilize without being degraded by heat.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In chemical ionization (CI), the analyte is ionized by a chemical reaction with an ionized reagent gas (itself ionized by some technique, such as by EI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyte gas and the reagent gas intersect, and react.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The reaction then produces ionized analyte fragments by various mechanisms, including proton transfer, electron transfer, and adduct formation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion is then accelerated electrostatically, as in EI.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] CI ion sources are similar to EI sources, and most modern mass spectrometers can switch from EI to CI mode in minutes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] To ensure efficiency, the amount of reagent is much higher than the analyte.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, a large amount of reagent ions would end up in the mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is usually handled by only measuring the part of the spectrogram with *m/z* above those of the main species in the reagent ion stream.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Common ionizing reagents for CI-MS include methane, ammonia, isobutane, and methanol.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The proton affinity of the reagent gas and of the sample should be matched to ensure efficient ionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too high, ionization is inefficient.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too low, fragmentation is excessive.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Electrospray ionization (ESI) and thermospray ionization (TSI) are suited for high molecular weight biomolecules and other labile or nonvolatile compounds, and especially in a LC-MS system.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In both cases, the analyte is in a solution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solution is sprayed out, by either electrospraying or thermospraying, into a stream of mist, which then evaporates into an ion stream.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] TSI has been supplanted by ESI for most purposes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In TSI, the solution enters a heated capillary, producing a spray of droplets.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solvent evaporates, leaving ionized analytes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In ESI, the solution enters a capillary held at a high voltage (usually 2-5 kV), producing an electrospray into a heated chamber against a counterflow of a drying gas (usually nitrogen).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The charge density increases on a droplet as it evaporates, until the electrostatic energy overcomes the surface tension energy, exploding the droplet.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This process repeats, ending with an ion stream without the solvent.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Unlike in TSI, the analyte ions produced by ESI may carry a different amount of charge than the same analyte would carry in the solution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] That is, an analyte that is naturally occurring as M+ in the solution may end up becoming a stream of ions containing a mixture of M+, M2+, M3+, etc.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical proteins can carry many protons due to the presence of basic amino acid side chains, resulting in peaks at *m/z* = 600–2000 for proteins with a molecular weight ~200,000 Da.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is convenient, since it means the ion would not exceed the *m/z* limits on typical mass analyzers.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption ionization (DI) is a family of ionization techniques.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The main examples are secondary-ion mass spectrometry (SIMS), fast atom bombardment (FAB), and matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In DI, the sample is dissolved or dispersed in a matrix, and bombarded by a high-energy (1-10 keV) beam of ions (SIMS), neutral atoms (FAB), or photons (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The beam ionizes and expels (desorbs) some sample molecules off the matrix.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The matrix should be nonvolatile and relatively inert, so that it would not react with the analyte.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It should also be a good electrolyte to allow ion formation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ionized fragments of the matrix itself forms usually have $m/z\lesssim 600$ , so the spectrogram usually filters out that segment.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] SIMS uses an ion beam, usually Ar+ or Cs+.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] FAB uses a neutral atom beam, usually Ar or Xe.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For SIMS and FAB, if the matrix compound is more acidic than the analyte, then predominantly (M + H)+ forms formed, and conversely (M − H)−.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Also possibly forming (M + Na)+, (M + K)+, etc, if the matrix is contaminated incidentally (adventitiously) by sodium, potassium, etc.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical matrix materials include glycerol, thioglycerol, 3-nitrobenzyl alcohol, diethanolamine, triethanolamine, and dithiothreitol-dithioerythritol mixture.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are usually used to analyze polypeptides and oligonucleotides up to 20 kDa.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE uses a photon beam, usually the soft-UV 337 nm nitrogen laser.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can also use an infrared (IR) laser for direct analysis of samples contained in gels or thin-layer chromatography (TLC) plates.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE can analyze small polymers (~1 kDa), to oligosaccharides, oligonucleotides and polypeptides, antibodies, up to small proteins (~300 kDa).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is highly sensitive, requiring only femtomoles of sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption/ionization on silicon (DIOS) is similar to MALDE, but without the matrix.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is deposited directly on a nanostructured (porous silicon) surface and the sample desorbed directly from the nanostructured surface through the adsorption of laser light energy.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] DIOS has been used to analyze organic molecules, metabolites, biomolecules and peptides, and, ultimately, to image tissues and cells.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Inductively coupled plasma (ICP) sources are used primarily for cation analysis of a wide array of sample types.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In this source, a plasma that is electrically neutral overall, but that has had a substantial fraction of its atoms ionized by high temperature, is used to atomize introduced sample molecules and to further strip the outer electrons from those atoms.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The plasma is usually generated from argon gas, since the first ionization energy of argon atoms is higher than the first of any other elements except He, F and Ne, but lower than the second ionization energy of all except the most electropositive metals.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The heating is achieved by a radio-frequency current passed through a coil surrounding the plasma.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Photoionization can be used in experiments which seek to use mass spectrometry as a means of resolving chemical kinetics mechanisms and isomeric product branching.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In such instances a high energy photon, either X-ray or uv, is used to dissociate stable gaseous molecules in a carrier gas of He or Ar.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In instances where a synchrotron light source is utilized, a tuneable photon energy can be utilized to acquire a photoionization efficiency curve which can be used in conjunction with the charge ratio *m/z* to fingerprint molecular and ionic species.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] More recently atmospheric pressure photoionization (APPI) has been developed to ionize molecules mostly as effluents of LC-MS systems.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some applications for ambient ionization include environmental applications as well as clinical applications.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In these techniques, ions form in an ion source outside the mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sampling becomes easy as the samples don't need previous separation nor preparation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Others include glow discharge, field desorption (FD), spark ionization and thermal ionization (TIMS).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass analyzers separate the ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many types of mass analyzers, using either static or dynamic fields, magnetic or electric fields.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each analyzer type has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many mass spectrometers use two or more mass analyzers for tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the more common mass analyzers listed below, there are others designed for special situations.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] of motion in the non-relativistic case, i.e. valid only at ion velocity much lower than the speed of light).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This differential equation is the classic equation of motion for charged particles.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Together with the particle's initial conditions, it completely determines the particle's motion in space and time in terms of *m/Q*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus mass spectrometers could be thought of as "mass-to-charge spectrometers".
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] When presenting data, it is common to use the (officially) dimensionless *m/z*, where z is the number of elementary charges (*e*) on the ion (z=Q/e).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This quantity, although it is informally called the mass-to-charge ratio, more accurately speaking represents the ratio of the mass number and the charge number, *z*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are several important analyzer characteristics.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass resolving power** $\Delta (m/z)$ is the just detectable difference in *m/z*, at that particular *m/z*, usually measured measured in milli mass units (mDa).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In particular, the resolution may be different at different *m/z*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is usually operationalized as the full width at half maximum a peak at that given *m/z*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A "high-resolution" mass analyzer typically has resolution >1 million.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, that means it can resolve two peaks at ~1 kDa, differing by just ~1 mDa.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **absolute accuracy** is the ratio of the *m/z* measurement error to the true *m/z*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass range** is the range of *m/z* that a given analyzer can analyze.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **speed** is the number of spectra lines per unit time that can be generated.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, higher resolution requires lower speed, and vice versa.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some mass spectrometers, such as the Fourier transform spectrometers, allow a continuous tradeoff between speed and resolution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A sector-type mass analyzer uses a static electric and/or magnetic field to control the path of the ion beam.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common type uses a magnetic field.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a simplified case, the field is a constant field B , and we have an ion of mass m and charge $ze$ that enters the field perpendicularly at velocity v .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Then, in the field, the ion undergoes circular motion of radius $R={\tfrac {v(m/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer has accelerated the ion under a known voltage V , then the kinetic energy of the ion is $KE=zeV={\tfrac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ , giving $m/z={\frac {eR^{2}B^{2}}{2V}}$ Thus, the single input ion beam is analyzed into a fan of ion beams, the higher m/z ions turning at a larger radius.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can then select for one m/z by using a moving narrow slit.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can also use a fixed narrow slit, but vary V or B .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If there is just a single detector, then the analyzer can sweep across the mass spectrum one slit at a time.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] With multiple detectors, the speed of analysis increases.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A pure magnetic sector analyzer can achieve resolution ~10,000.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] With an added electrostatic focusing field before or after the magnetic sector, the analyzer can achieve resolution ~100,000.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Particularly unstable ions may disintegrate while passing through the analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If it undergoes the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts) when entering the analyzer, it would undergo a circular motion of radius $R'={\tfrac {v(m'/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This would then show up in the resulting spectrogram as a peak that is *apparently* made by an ion with $(m^{*}/z)=({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since there is no actual ion with mass $m^{*}$ , this is called an abnormal peak, or a **metastable ion peak**.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In general, a meta stable ion peak is a broad peak centered at a highly non-integer value of $m^{*}/z$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The existence of a metastable ion peak at $({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ is strong evidence that two ions of masses $m/z,m'/z$ are in fact related by the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The time-of-flight (TOF) analyzer takes as input a short *pulse* of ions, and lets it fly through a long vacuum tube.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions with different m/z would arrive at the end of the tube at different times, thus analyzing them.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions must enter the tube as pulses, because otherwise the TOF cannot be measured.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer outputs a continuous stream of ions, then it must be cut up into ion pulses, by methods such as a fast mechanical shutter, an oscillating electric field plus a narrow slit, etc.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The MALDI ionizer is particularly well-suited for TOF analyzer, since the laser used in MALDI is usually a high-intensity pulse laser.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDI-TOF has allowed measurement of mass spetrograms using only a few attomoles of material.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, let the length of the analyzer be L , then the time taken for an ion of velocity v to pass through the analyzer is $t=L/v$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In that case, we have $m/z=(m/z)_{0}+{\frac {4eVt_{0}}{L^{2}}}\delta t$ This means that the signal can be measured by an oscilloscope in trigger mode.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, the first GC-MS was done in 1950 using an oscilloscope.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The experimenters took quick photos of the oscilloscope screen for each component exiting the gas chromatography machine.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This distribution in velocities broadens the peaks shown on the count vs *m/z* plot, but will generally not change the central location of the peaks, since the starting velocity of ions is generally centered at zero.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] To fix this problem, time-lag focusing/delayed extraction has been coupled with TOF-MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ions do not start at identical kinetic energies, then some ions may lag behind higher kinetic energy ions decreasing resolution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Reflectron geometries are commonly employed to correct this problem.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Longer tubes result in higher resolution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector doubles the effective tube length.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector-TOF can reach a resolution of several thousands.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For their low resolution, TOF mass spectrometers makes up for it in speed.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are particularly useful in chemical kinetics studies.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can study rapid reactions such as combustion and explosions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A quadrupole mass analyzers uses four parallel metal rods to create a quadrupole electrical field oscillating at radio frequency (RF), to selectively stabilize or destabilize the paths of ions passing through.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] With each oscillation pattern, the ions passing through would undergo a helical motion.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ion has *m/z* within a certain range, the helical motion is stable.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Otherwise, the helical motion will increase in amplitude until the ion collides with the rods.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This means that only ions with m/z within a narrow range can go through it.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The full spectrogram can be swept through by changing the potentials on the rods, continuously or in a succession of discrete hops.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are typically of low resolution ~1000, but they are cheap and small, so are good for "desktop" mass spectrometers.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole mass filter is closely related to the quadrupole ion trap, particularly the linear quadrupole ion trap except that it is designed to pass the untrapped ions rather than collect the trapped ones, and is for that reason referred to as a **transmission quadrupole**.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap itself can be used as an analyzer, as in ion trap analyzers.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A common variation of the transmission quadrupole is the triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The "triple quad" has three consecutive quadrupole stages, the first acting as a mass filter to transmit a particular incoming ion to the second quadrupole, a collision chamber, wherein that ion can be broken into fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The third quadrupole also acts as a mass filter, to transmit a particular fragment ion to the detector.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a kind of MS/MS, and so it can perform various scan types characteristic of MS/MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A magnetically enhanced quadrupole mass analyzer has an additional magnetic field, axial or transverse.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap works on the same physical principles as the quadrupole mass analyzer, but the ions are trapped and sequentially ejected.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are trapped in a mainly quadrupole RF field, in a space defined by a ring electrode (usually connected to the main RF potential) between two endcap electrodes (typically connected to DC or auxiliary AC potentials).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is ionized either internally (e.g. with an electron or laser beam), or externally, in which case the ions are often introduced through an aperture in an endcap electrode.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many mass/charge separation and isolation methods but the most commonly used is the mass instability mode in which the RF potential is ramped so that the orbit of ions with a mass *a* > *b* are stable while ions with mass *b* become unstable and are ejected on the *z*-axis onto a detector.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are also non-destructive analysis methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The cylindrical ion trap mass spectrometer (CIT) is a derivative of the quadrupole ion trap where the electrodes are formed from flat rings rather than hyperbolic shaped electrodes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The architecture lends itself well to miniaturization because as the size of a trap is reduced, the shape of the electric field near the center of the trap, the region where the ions are trapped, forms a shape similar to that of a hyperbolic trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A linear quadrupole ion trap is similar to a quadrupole ion trap, but it traps ions in a two dimensional quadrupole field, instead of a three-dimensional quadrupole field as in a 3D quadrupole ion trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thermo Fisher's LTQ ("linear trap quadrupole") is an example of the linear ion trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A toroidal ion trap can be visualized as a linear quadrupole curved around and connected at the ends or as a cross-section of a 3D ion trap rotated on edge to form the toroid, donut-shaped trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The trap can store large volumes of ions by distributing them throughout the ring-like trap structure.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This toroidal shaped trap is a configuration that allows the increased miniaturization of an ion trap mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Additionally, all ions are stored in the same trapping field and ejected together simplifying detection that can be complicated with array configurations due to variations in detector alignment and machining of the arrays.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] As with the toroidal trap, linear traps and 3D quadrupole ion traps are the most commonly miniaturized mass analyzers due to their high sensitivity, tolerance for mTorr pressure, and capabilities for single analyzer tandem mass spectrometry (e.g. product ion scans).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Fourier-transform mass spectrometry (FTMS), or more precisely Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (FT-ICR MS), measures mass by detecting the image current produced by ions spiralling in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Instead of measuring the deflection of ions with a detector such as an electron multiplier, the ions are injected into a Penning trap (a static electric/magnetic ion trap) where they effectively form part of a circuit.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Detectors at fixed positions in space measure the electrical signal of ions which pass near them over time, producing a periodic signal.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since the frequency of an ion's cycling is determined by its *m/z* ratio, this can be deconvoluted by Fourier transform on the signal.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ion cyclotron resonance (ICR) is an older mass analysis technique.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is similar to FTMS, in that the ions undergo cyclotron resonane.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, the ions are detected with a traditional detector.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions trapped in a Penning trap are excited by an RF electric field until they impact the wall of the trap, where the detector is located.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions of different mass are resolved according to impact time.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] FTMS is generally the most sensitive analyzer on the market, achieving resolution ~1 million.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It achieves such high resolution, since each ion is "counted" multiple times by the spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] From the perspective of the uncertainty principle of signal processing, an oscillating signal that is highly *delocalized* in time is also highly *localized* in frequency.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitrap analyzers are similar to FTMS analyzers.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are electrostatically trapped in an orbit around a central, spindle shaped electrode.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrode confines the ions so that they both orbit around the central electrode and oscillate back and forth along the central electrode's long axis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This oscillation generates an image current in the detector plates which is recorded by the instrument.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The frequencies of these image currents depend on the mass-to-charge ratios of the ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectra are obtained by Fourier transformation of the recorded image currents.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitraps have a high mass accuracy, high sensitivity and a good dynamic range.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some chemical species have the same chemical composition, but different isotopes (isotopomers).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can be distinguished by a very basic analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, isotopes were discovered in 1922, very early in the history of mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, two chemical species can have the same number of nucleons (neutrons and protons).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C3 and SH4 both have 36 nucleons.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can still be distinguished, since proton and neutron mass differ by 1.4 mDa, and since different nuclei have different binding energy, which by $E=mc^{2}$ results in a different mass.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The net result is that C3 and S1H4 differ by 3.4 mDa.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Even smaller differences are achievable by carefully matching isotopes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C4 and S1H313C1 differ by 1.1 mDa.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such differences can be resolved by high resolution mass spectrometry, which reaches resolution >1 million, sufficient to resolve ~1 mDa difference at *m/z* ~ 1000.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques for high resolution MS, but the highest resolution is achieved by FTMS with high magnetic field.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] With increasing magnetic field strength, the resolution and spectral acquisition speed increases linearly, while mass accuracy and dynamic range increases quadratically.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the highest resolution is achieved by high field FTMS, up to 21 Tesla.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It reaches resolution >2.7 million at m/z ~ 400, and mass measurement accuracy < 80 ppb.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are often employed in geochemical and petrochemical studies, since there is a lot of money in petroleum industry, and petroleum composition is highly complex.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another application is in isotopic analysis of large proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two proteins differing by a single isotopic atom are separated by $\Delta m\approx 1$ , requiring a resolution of $m/\Delta m$ to resolve.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For large proteins with m > 100 kDa and z ~ 50, such as monoclonal antibodies, this requires an analyzer that achieves resolving power > 100,000 at m/z ~ 2000.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] High resolution FTMS is also very sensitive as a detector.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] It has allowed detecting proteins in the 8–20 kDa range at a sample concentration of ~30 zeptomole (i.e. about 20,000 *individual* molecules).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] When the mass of a single ion species is to be measured, the highest precision achievable is via Penning-type traps.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The PENTATRAP for example measures the mass of long-lived, highly charged, heavy ions, to a precision of $m/\Delta m>10^{11}$ .
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is sufficiently sensitive to directly measure the energy of metastable electronic states to an accuracy of ~1 eV via the mass-energy equation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The final element of the mass spectrometer is the detector.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector records either the charge induced or the current produced when an ion passes by or hits a surface.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a scanning instrument, the signal produced in the detector during the course of the scan versus where the instrument is in the scan (at what *m/Q*) will produce a mass spectrum, a record of ions as a function of *m/Q*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **linear dynamic range** is the range over which the detector signal is linear with analyte concentration.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, some type of electron multiplier is used, though other detectors including Faraday cups and ion-to-photon detectors are also used.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Because the number of ions leaving the mass analyzer at a particular instant is typically quite small, considerable amplification is often necessary to get a signal.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Microchannel plate detectors are commonly used in modern commercial instruments.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In FTMS and Orbitraps, the detector consists of a pair of metal surfaces within the mass analyzer/ion trap region which the ions only pass near as they oscillate.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] No direct current is produced, only a weak AC image current is produced in a circuit between the electrodes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other inductive detectors have also been used.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A tandem mass spectrometer is one capable of multiple rounds of mass spectrometry, usually separated by some form of molecule fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, one mass analyzer can isolate one peptide from many entering a mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A collision cell then stabilizes the peptide ions while they collide with a gas, causing them to fragment by collision-induced dissociation (CID).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] A further mass analyzer then sorts the fragments produced from the peptides.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem MS can also be done in a single mass analyzer over time, as in a quadrupole ion trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] An important application using tandem mass spectrometry is in protein identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem mass spectrometry enables a variety of experimental sequences.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many commercial mass spectrometers are designed to expedite the execution of such routine sequences as selected reaction monitoring, precursor ion scanning, product ion scanning, and neutral loss scanning.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another type of tandem mass spectrometry used for radiocarbon dating is accelerator mass spectrometry, which uses very high voltages, usually in the mega-volt range, to accelerate negative ions into a type of tandem mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **METLIN Metabolite and Chemical Entity Database** is the largest repository of experimental tandem mass spectrometry data acquired from standards.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] The tandem mass spectrometry data on over 960,000 molecular standards (as of October 2025) is provided to facilitate the identification of chemical entities from tandem mass spectrometry experiments.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the identification of known molecules it is also useful for identifying unknowns using its similarity searching/analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] All tandem mass spectrometry data comes from the experimental analysis of standards at multiple collision energies and in both positive and negative ionization modes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] When a specific combination of source, analyzer, and detector becomes conventional in practice, a compound acronym may arise to designate it succinctly.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] One example is MALDI-TOF, which refers to a combination of a matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization source with a time-of-flight mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other examples include inductively coupled plasma-mass spectrometry (ICP-MS), accelerator mass spectrometry, thermal ionization-mass spectrometry (TIMS) and spark source mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] Certain applications of mass spectrometry have developed monikers that although strictly speaking would seem to refer to a broad application, in practice have come instead to connote a specific or a limited number of instrument configurations.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p01] An example of this is isotope-ratio mass spectrometry, which refers in practice to the use of a limited number of sector based mass analyzers; this name is used to refer to both the application and the instrument used for the application.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important enhancement to the mass resolving and mass determining capabilities of mass spectrometry is using it in tandem with chromatographic and other separation techniques.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A common combination is gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC/MS or GC-MS).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this technique, a gas chromatograph is used to separate different compounds.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This stream of separated compounds is fed online into the ion source, a metallic filament to which voltage is applied.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This filament emits electrons which ionize the compounds.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The ions can then further fragment, yielding predictable patterns.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Intact ions and fragments pass into the mass spectrometer's analyzer and are eventually detected.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, the high temperatures (300 °C) used in the GC-MS injection port (and oven) can result in thermal degradation of injected molecules, thus resulting in the measurement of degradation products instead of the actual molecule(s) of interest.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Similarly to gas chromatography MS (GC-MS), liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC/MS or LC-MS) separates compounds chromatographically before they are introduced to the ion source and mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] It differs from GC-MS in that the mobile phase is liquid, usually a mixture of water and organic solvents, instead of gas.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most commonly, an electrospray ionization source is used in LC-MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other popular and commercially available LC-MS ion sources are atmospheric pressure chemical ionization and atmospheric pressure photoionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] There are also some newly developed ionization techniques like laser spray.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Capillary electrophoresis–mass spectrometry (CE-MS) is a technique that combines the liquid separation process of capillary electrophoresis with mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] CE-MS is typically coupled to electrospray ionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion mobility spectrometry-mass spectrometry (IMS/MS or IMMS) is a technique where ions are first separated by drift time through some neutral gas under an applied electrical potential gradient before being introduced into a mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Drift time is a measure of the collisional cross section relative to the charge of the ion.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS (the time over which the experiment takes place) is longer than most mass spectrometric techniques, such that the mass spectrometer can sample along the course of the IMS separation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This produces data about the IMS separation and the mass-to-charge ratio of the ions in a manner similar to LC-MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS is short relative to liquid chromatography or gas chromatography separations and can thus be coupled to such techniques, producing triple modalities such as LC/IMS/MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry produces various types of data.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common data representation is the mass spectrum.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Certain types of mass spectrometry data are best represented as a mass chromatogram.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Types of chromatograms include selected ion monitoring (SIM), total ion current (TIC), and selected reaction monitoring, among many others.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other types of mass spectrometry data are well represented as a three-dimensional contour map.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this form, the mass-to-charge, *m/z* is on the *x*-axis, intensity the *y*-axis, and an additional experimental parameter, such as time, is recorded on the *z*-axis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry data analysis is specific to the type of experiment producing the data.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] General subdivisions of data are fundamental to understanding any data.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Many mass spectrometers work in either *negative ion mode* or *positive ion mode*.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is very important to know whether the observed ions are negatively or positively charged.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is often important in determining the neutral mass but it also indicates something about the nature of the molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Different types of ion source result in different arrays of fragments produced from the original molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] An electron ionization source produces many fragments and mostly single-charged (1-) radicals (odd number of electrons), whereas an electrospray source usually produces non-radical quasimolecular ions that are frequently multiply charged.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry purposely produces fragment ions post-source and can drastically change the sort of data achieved by an experiment.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Knowledge of the origin of a sample can provide insight into the component molecules of the sample and their fragmentations.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A sample from a synthesis/manufacturing process will probably contain impurities chemically related to the target component.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A crudely prepared biological sample will probably contain a certain amount of salt, which may form adducts with the analyte molecules in certain analyses.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Results can also depend heavily on sample preparation and how it was run/introduced.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important example is the issue of which matrix is used for MALDI spotting, since much of the energetics of the desorption/ionization event is controlled by the matrix rather than the laser power.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Sometimes samples are spiked with sodium or another ion-carrying species to produce adducts rather than a protonated species.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry can measure molar mass, molecular structure, and sample purity.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Each of these questions requires a different experimental procedure; therefore, adequate definition of the experimental goal is a prerequisite for collecting the proper data and successfully interpreting it.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Since the precise structure or peptide sequence of a molecule is deciphered through the set of fragment masses, the interpretation of mass spectra requires combined use of various techniques.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Usually the first strategy for identifying an unknown compound is to compare its experimental mass spectrum against a library of mass spectra.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] If no matches result from the search, then manual interpretation or software assisted interpretation of mass spectra must be performed.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Computer simulation of ionization and fragmentation processes occurring in mass spectrometer is the primary tool for assigning structure or peptide sequence to a molecule.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] An *a priori* structural information is fragmented *in silico* and the resulting pattern is compared with observed spectrum.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Such simulation is often supported by a fragmentation library that contains published patterns of known decomposition reactions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Software taking advantage of this idea has been developed for both small molecules and proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Analysis of mass spectra can also be spectra with accurate mass.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A mass-to-charge ratio value (*m/z*) with only integer precision can represent an immense number of theoretically possible ion structures; however, more precise mass figures significantly reduce the number of candidate molecular formulas.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer algorithm called formula generator calculates all molecular formulas that theoretically fit a given mass with specified tolerance.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry has both qualitative and quantitative uses.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] These include identifying unknown compounds, determining the isotopic composition of elements in a molecule, and determining the structure of a compound by observing its fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other uses include quantifying the amount of a compound in a sample or studying the fundamentals of gas phase ion chemistry (the chemistry of ions and neutrals in a vacuum).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] MS is now commonly used in analytical laboratories that study physical, chemical, or biological properties of a great variety of compounds.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Quantification can be relative (analyzed relative to a reference sample) or absolute (analyzed using a standard curve method).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A few of the disadvantages of the method is that it often fails to distinguish between optical and geometrical isomers and the positions of substituent in o-, m- and p- positions in an aromatic ring.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also, its scope is limited in identifying hydrocarbons that produce similar fragmented ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is also used to determine the isotopic composition of elements within a sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Differences in mass among isotopes of an element are very small, and the less abundant isotopes of an element are typically very rare, so a very sensitive instrument is required.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] For the measurement of light elements (e.g.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] H,C,N,O,S), isotope ratio mass spectrometers usually use a single magnet to bend a beam of ionized particles towards a series of Faraday cups which convert particle impacts to electric current.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A fast on-line analysis of deuterium content of water can be done using flowing afterglow mass spectrometry, FA-MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Probably the most sensitive and accurate mass spectrometer for this purpose is the accelerator mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is because it provides ultimate sensitivity, capable of measuring individual atoms and measuring nuclides with a dynamic range of ~1015 relative to the major stable isotope.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Isotopic signatures can serve as markers of a variety of processes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some isotope ratios are used to determine the age of materials for example as in carbon dating.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Labeling with stable isotopes is also used for protein quantification (see protein characterization below).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Membrane-introduction mass spectrometry combines the isotope ratio mass spectrometry with a reaction chamber/cell separated by a gas-permeable membrane.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method allows the study of gases as they evolve in solution.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method has been extensively used for the study of the production of oxygen by Photosystem II.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Another technique with applications in trace gas analysis field is secondary electrospray ionization (SESI-MS), which is a variant of electrospray ionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] SESI consist of an electrospray plume of pure acidified solvent that interacts with neutral vapors.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Vapor molecules get ionized at atmospheric pressure when charge is transferred from the ions formed in the electrospray to the molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] One advantage of this approach is that it is compatible with most ESI-MS systems.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A residual gas analyzer (RGA) is a small and usually rugged mass spectrometer, typically designed for process control and contamination monitoring in vacuum systems.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] When constructed as a quadrupole mass analyzer, there exist two implementations, utilizing either an open ion source (OIS) or a closed ion source (CIS).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs may be found in high vacuum applications such as research chambers, surface science setups, accelerators, scanning microscopes, etc.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs are used in most cases to monitor the quality of the vacuum and easily detect minute traces of impurities in the low-pressure gas environment.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] These impurities can be measured down to $10^{-14}$ Torr levels, possessing sub-ppm detectability in the absence of background interferences.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs would also be used as sensitive in-situ leak detectors commonly using helium, isopropyl alcohol or other tracer molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] With vacuum systems pumped down to lower than $10^{-5}$ Torr—checking of the integrity of the vacuum seals and the quality of the vacuum—air leaks, virtual leaks and other contaminants at low levels may be detected before a process is initiated.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] An atom probe is an instrument that combines time-of-flight mass spectrometry and field-evaporation microscopy to map the location of individual atoms.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Pharmacokinetics is often studied using mass spectrometry because of the complex nature of the matrix (often blood or urine) and the need for high sensitivity to observe low dose and long time point data.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common instrumentation used in this application is LC-MS with a triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry is usually employed for added specificity.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Standard curves and internal standards are used for quantitation of usually a single pharmaceutical in the samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The samples represent different time points as a pharmaceutical is administered and then metabolized or cleared from the body.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Blank or t=0 samples taken before administration are important in determining background and ensuring data integrity with such complex sample matrices.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Much attention is paid to the linearity of the standard curve; however it is not uncommon to use curve fitting with more complex functions such as quadratics since the response of most mass spectrometers is less than linear across large concentration ranges.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] There is currently considerable interest in the use of very high sensitivity mass spectrometry for microdosing studies, which are seen as a promising alternative to animal experimentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Recent studies show that secondary electrospray ionization (SESI) is a powerful technique to monitor drug kinetics via breath analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Because breath is naturally produced, several datapoints can be readily collected.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This allows for the number of collected data-points to be greatly increased.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In animal studies, this approach SESI can reduce animal sacrifice.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In humans, SESI-MS non-invasive analysis of breath can help study the kinetics of drugs at a personalized level.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is an important method for the characterization and sequencing of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The two primary methods for ionization of whole proteins are electrospray ionization (ESI) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In keeping with the performance and mass range of available mass spectrometers, two approaches are used for characterizing proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the first, intact proteins are ionized by either of the two techniques described above, and then introduced to a mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This approach is referred to as "top-down" strategy of protein analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The top-down approach however is largely limited to low-throughput single-protein studies.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the second, proteins are enzymatically digested into smaller peptides using proteases such as trypsin or pepsin, either in solution or in gel after electrophoretic separation.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The collection of peptide products are often separated by chromatography prior to introduction to the mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] When the characteristic pattern of peptides is used for the identification of the protein the method is called peptide mass fingerprinting (PMF), if the identification is performed using the sequence data determined in tandem MS analysis it is called de novo peptide sequencing.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] These procedures of protein analysis are also referred to as the "bottom-up" approach, and have also been used to analyse the distribution and position of post-translational modifications such as phosphorylation on proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A third approach is also beginning to be used, this intermediate "middle-down" approach involves analyzing proteolytic peptides that are larger than the typical tryptic peptide.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] As a standard method for analysis, mass spectrometers have reached other planets and moons.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Two were taken to Mars by the Viking program.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In early 2005 the Cassini–Huygens mission delivered a specialized GC-MS instrument aboard the Huygens probe through the atmosphere of Titan, the largest moon of the planet Saturn.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] This instrument analyzed atmospheric samples along its descent trajectory and was able to vaporize and analyze samples of Titan's frozen, hydrocarbon covered surface once the probe had landed.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] These measurements compare the abundance of isotope(s) of each particle comparatively to earth's natural abundance.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also on board the Cassini–Huygens spacecraft was an ion and neutral mass spectrometer which had been taking measurements of Titan's atmospheric composition as well as the composition of Enceladus' plumes.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A Thermal and Evolved Gas Analyzer mass spectrometer was carried by the Mars Phoenix Lander launched in 2007.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers are also widely used in space missions to measure the composition of plasmas.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] For example, the Cassini spacecraft carried the Cassini Plasma Spectrometer (CAPS), which measured the mass of ions in Saturn's magnetosphere.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers were used in hospitals for respiratory gas analysis beginning around 1975 through the end of the century.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some are probably still in use but none are currently being manufactured.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Found mostly in the operating room, they were a part of a complex system, in which respired gas samples from patients undergoing anesthesia were drawn into the instrument through a valve mechanism designed to sequentially connect up to 32 rooms to the mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer directed all operations of the system.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The data collected from the mass spectrometer was delivered to the individual rooms for the anesthesiologist to use.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The uniqueness of this magnetic sector mass spectrometer may have been the fact that a plane of detectors, each purposely positioned to collect all of the ion species expected to be in the samples, allowed the instrument to simultaneously report all of the gases respired by the patient.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Although the mass range was limited to slightly over 120 u, fragmentation of some of the heavier molecules negated the need for a higher detection limit.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The primary function of mass spectrometry is as a tool for chemical analyses based on detection and quantification of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, mass spectrometry also shows promise for material synthesis.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion soft landing is characterized by deposition of intact species on surfaces at low kinetic energies which precludes the fragmentation of the incident species.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] The soft landing technique was first reported in 1977 for the reaction of low energy sulfur containing ions on a lead surface.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most mass spectrometers measure the mass-to-charge ratio; the actual mass can be found only if the charge is known.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] For smaller molecules the charge can be determined from the spacing of isotope peaks, but for very large biomolecules and particles (in the megadalton range) resolution may not be adequate to separate isotope peaks, and thus the mass cannot be determined.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] In charge detection mass spectrometry (CDMS), the charge of an individual ion/particle is measured directly (alongside its mass-to-charge ratio) and therefore the true mass is known.
[src:proteomics-bio/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is a single-particle technique, but to produce more precise and accurate results, the data from many individually-measured ions can be combined.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The advantage of this method is that only the masses of the peptides have to be known.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A disadvantage is that the protein sequence has to be present in the database of interest.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Additionally most PMF algorithms assume that the peptides come from a single protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The presence of a mixture can significantly complicate the analysis and potentially compromise the results.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Typical for the PMF-based protein identification is the requirement for an isolated protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Mixtures exceeding a number of 2–3 proteins typically require the additional use of MS/MS-based protein identification to achieve sufficient specificity of identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Therefore, typical PMF samples are isolated proteins from two-dimensional gel electrophoresis (2D gels) or isolated SDS-PAGE bands.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Additional analyses by MS/MS can either be direct, e.g., MALDI-TOF/TOF analysis or downstream nanoLC-ESI-MS/MS analysis of gel spot eluates.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Due to the long, tedious process of analyzing proteins, peptide mass fingerprinting was developed.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Edman degradation was used in protein analysis, and it required almost an hour to analyze one amino acid residue.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] SDS-PAGE was also used to separate proteins in very complex mixtures, which also employed methods of electroblotting and staining.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Then, bands would be extracted from the gel and sequenced, automatically.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A recurring problem in the process was that interfering proteins would also purify with the protein of interest.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The sequences of these interfering proteins were compiled into what came to known as the Dayhoff database.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Ultimately, having the sequences of these known protein contaminants in databases decreased instrument time and expenses involved in protein analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Protein samples can be derived from SDS-PAGE or reversed phase HPLC, and are then subject to some chemical modifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Disulfide bridges in proteins are reduced and cysteine amino acids are carbamidomethylated chemically or acrylamidated during the gel electrophoresis.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Then the proteins are cut into several fragments using proteolytic enzymes such as trypsin, chymotrypsin or Glu-C.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A typical sample:protease ratio is 50:1.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The proteolysis is typically carried out overnight and the resulting peptides are extracted with acetonitrile and dried under vacuum.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The peptides are then dissolved in a small amount of distilled water or further concentrated and purified and are ready for mass spectrometric analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The digested protein can be analyzed with different types of mass spectrometers such as ESI-TOF or MALDI-TOF.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] MALDI-TOF is often the preferred instrument because it allows a high sample throughput and several proteins can be analyzed in a single experiment, if complemented by MS/MS analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] LC/ESI-MS and CE/ESI-MS are also great techniques for peptide mass fingerprinting.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] A small fraction of the peptide (usually 1 microliter or less) is pipetted onto a MALDI target and a chemical called a matrix is added to the peptide mix.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Common matrices are sinapinic acid, Alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid, and 2,3-Dihydroxybenzoic acid.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The matrix molecules are required for the desorption of the peptide molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Matrix and peptide molecules co-crystallize on the MALDI target and are ready to be analyzed.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] There is one predominantly MALDI-MS sample preparation technique, namely dried droplet technique.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The target is inserted into the vacuum chamber of the mass spectrometer and the desorption and ionisation of the polypeptide fragments is initiated by a pulsed laser beam which transfers high amounts of energy into the matrix molecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The energy transfer is sufficient to promote the ionisation and transition of matrix molecules and peptides from the solid phase into the gas phase.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The ions are accelerated in the electric field of the mass spectrometer and fly towards an ion detector where their arrival is detected as an electric signal.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Their mass-to-charge ratio is proportional to their time of flight (TOF) in the drift tube and can be calculated accordingly.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Coupling ESI with capillary LC can separate peptides from protein digests, while obtaining their molecular masses at the same time.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Capillary electrophoresis coupled with ESI-MS is another technique; however, it works best when analyzing small amounts of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The mass spectrometric analysis produces a list of molecular weights which is often called a peak list.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The peptide masses are compared to protein databases such as Swissprot, which contain protein sequence information.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] Software performs *in silico* digests on proteins in the database with the same enzyme (e.g. trypsin) used in the chemical cleavage reaction.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The mass of these peptides is then calculated and compared to the peak list of measured masses.
[src:proteomics-bio/peptide-mass-fingerprinting] The results are statistically analyzed and possible matches are returned in a results table.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The two primary methods used for the ionization of protein in mass spectrometry are electrospray ionization (ESI) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] These ionization techniques are used in conjunction with mass analyzers such as tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In general, the proteins are analyzed either in a "top-down" approach in which proteins are analyzed intact, or a "bottom-up" approach in which protein are first digested into fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] An intermediate "middle-down" approach in which larger peptide fragments are analyzed may also sometimes be used.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The application of mass spectrometry to study proteins became popularized in the 1980s after the development of MALDI and ESI.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] These ionization techniques have played a significant role in the characterization of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] (MALDI) Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization was coined in the late 1980s by Franz Hillenkamp and Michael Karas.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Hillenkamp, Karas and their fellow researchers were able to ionize the amino acid alanine by mixing it with the amino acid tryptophan and irradiated with a pulse 266 nm laser.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Though important, the breakthrough did not come until 1987.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In 1987, Koichi Tanaka used the "ultra fine metal plus liquid matrix method" and ionized biomolecules the size of 34,472 Da protein carboxypeptidase-A.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In 1968, Malcolm Dole reported the first use of electrospray ionization with mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Around the same time MALDI became popularized, John Bennett Fenn was cited for the development of electrospray ionization.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Koichi Tanaka received the 2002 Nobel Prize in Chemistry alongside John Fenn, and Kurt Wüthrich "for the development of methods for identification and structure analyses of biological macromolecules." These ionization methods have greatly facilitated the study of proteins by mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Consequently, protein mass spectrometry now plays a leading role in protein characterization.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Mass spectrometry of proteins requires that the proteins in solution or solid state be turned into an ionized form in the gas phase before they are injected and accelerated in an electric or magnetic field for analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The two primary methods for ionization of proteins are electrospray ionization (ESI) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In electrospray, the ions are created from proteins in solution, and it allows fragile molecules to be ionized intact, sometimes preserving non-covalent interactions.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In MALDI, the proteins are embedded within a matrix normally in a solid form, and ions are created by pulses of laser light.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Electrospray produces more multiply-charged ions than MALDI, allowing for measurement of high mass protein and better fragmentation for identification, while MALDI is fast and less likely to be affected by contaminants, buffers and additives.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Whole-protein mass analysis is primarily conducted using either time-of-flight (TOF) MS, or Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] These two types of instrument are preferable here because of their wide mass range, and in the case of FT-ICR, its high mass accuracy.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Electrospray ionization of a protein often results in generation of multiple charged species of 800 < *m/z* < 2000 and the resultant spectrum can be deconvoluted to determine the protein's average mass to within 50 ppm or better using TOF or ion-trap instruments.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Mass analysis of proteolytic peptides is a popular method of protein characterization, as cheaper instrument designs can be used for characterization.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Additionally, sample preparation is easier once whole proteins have been digested into smaller peptide fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The most widely used instrument for peptide mass analysis are the MALDI-TOF instruments as they permit the acquisition of peptide mass fingerprints (PMFs) at high pace (1 PMF can be analyzed in approx.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Multiple stage quadrupole-time-of-flight and the quadrupole ion trap also find use in this application.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS) is used to measure fragmentation spectra and identify proteins at high speed and accuracy.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Collision-induced dissociation is used in mainstream applications to generate a set of fragments from a specific peptide ion.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation process primarily gives rise to cleavage products that break along peptide bonds.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Because of this simplicity in fragmentation, it is possible to use the observed fragment masses to match with a database of predicted masses for one of many given peptide sequences.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Tandem MS of whole protein ions has been investigated recently using electron capture dissociation and has demonstrated extensive sequence information in principle but is not in common practice.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] This approach is referred to as "top-down" strategy of protein analysis as it involves starting with the whole mass and then pulling it apart.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The top-down approach however is mostly limited to low-throughput single-protein studies due to issues involved in handling whole proteins, their heterogeneity and the complexity of their analyses.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In the second approach, referred to as the "bottom-up" MS, proteins are enzymatically digested into smaller peptides using a protease such as trypsin.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Subsequently, these peptides are introduced into the mass spectrometer and identified by peptide mass fingerprinting or tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Hence, this approach uses identification at the peptide level to infer the existence of proteins pieced back together with *de novo* repeat detection.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The smaller and more uniform fragments are easier to analyze than intact proteins and can be also determined with high accuracy, this "bottom-up" approach is therefore the preferred method of studies in proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] A further approach that is beginning to be useful is the intermediate "middle-down" approach in which proteolytic peptides larger than the typical tryptic peptides are analyzed.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Proteins of interest are usually part of a complex mixture of multiple proteins and molecules, which co-exist in the biological medium.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] First, the two ionization techniques used for large molecules only work well when the mixture contains roughly equal amounts of material, while in biological samples, different proteins tend to be present in widely differing amounts.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] If such a mixture is ionized using electrospray or MALDI, the more abundant species have a tendency to "drown" or suppress signals from less abundant ones.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Second, mass spectrum from a complex mixture is very difficult to interpret due to the overwhelming number of mixture components.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] This is exacerbated by the fact that enzymatic digestion of a protein gives rise to a large number of peptide products.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In light of these problems, the methods of one- and two-dimensional gel electrophoresis and high performance liquid chromatography are widely used for separation of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The first method fractionates whole proteins via two-dimensional gel electrophoresis.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The first-dimension of 2D gel is isoelectric focusing (IEF).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In this dimension, the protein is separated by its isoelectric point (pI) and the second-dimension is SDS-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] This dimension separates the protein according to its molecular weight.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Once this step is completed in-gel digestion occurs.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In some situations, it may be necessary to combine both of these techniques.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Gel spots identified on a 2D Gel are usually attributable to one protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] If the identity of the protein is desired, usually the method of in-gel digestion is applied, where the protein spot of interest is excised, and digested proteolytically.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The peptide masses resulting from the digestion can be determined by mass spectrometry using peptide mass fingerprinting.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] If this information does not allow unequivocal identification of the protein, its peptides can be subject to tandem mass spectrometry for *de novo* sequencing.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Small changes in mass and charge can be detected with 2D-PAGE.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The disadvantages with this technique are its small dynamic range compared to other methods, some proteins are still difficult to separate due to their acidity, basicity, hydrophobicity, and size (too large or too small).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The second method, high performance liquid chromatography is used to fractionate peptides after enzymatic digestion.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Characterization of protein mixtures using HPLC/MS is also called shotgun proteomics and MuDPIT (Multi-Dimensional Protein Identification Technology).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] A peptide mixture that results from digestion of a protein mixture is fractionated by one or two steps of liquid chromatography.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The eluent from the chromatography stage can be either directly introduced to the mass spectrometer through electrospray ionization, or laid down on a series of small spots for later mass analysis using MALDI.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] There are two main ways MS is used to identify proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Peptide mass fingerprinting uses the masses of proteolytic peptides as input to a search of a database of predicted masses that would arise from digestion of a list of known proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] If a protein sequence in the reference list gives rise to a significant number of predicted masses that match the experimental values, there is some evidence that this protein was present in the original sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Purification steps therefore limit the throughput of the peptide mass fingerprinting approach.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Alternatively, peptides can be fragmented with MS/MS to more definitively identify them.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] MS is also the preferred method for the identification of post-translational modifications in proteins versus other approaches such as antibody-based methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] As *de novo* sequencing is based on mass and some amino acids have identical masses (e.g. leucine and isoleucine), accurate manual sequencing can be difficult.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Therefore, it may be necessary to utilize a sequence homology search application to work in tandem between a database search and *de novo* sequencing to address this inherent limitation.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Database searching has the advantage of quickly identifying sequences, provided they have already been documented in a database.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] An annotated peptide spectral library can also be used as a reference for protein/peptide identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] It offers the unique strength of reduced search space and increased specificity.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The limitations include spectra not included in the library will not be identified, spectra collected from different types of mass spectrometers can have quite distinct features, and reference spectra in the library may contain noise peaks, which may lead to false positive identifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] A number of different algorithmic approaches have been described to identify peptides and proteins from tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS), peptide *de novo* sequencing and sequence tag-based searching.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Antigen presentation is the first step in educating the immune system to recognize new pathogens.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] To this end, antigen presenting cells expose protein fragments via MHC molecules to the immune system.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Not all protein fragments bind, however, to the MHC molecules of a certain individual.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Using mass spectrometry, the true spectrum of molecules presented to the immune system can be determined.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Multiple methods allow for the quantitation of proteins by mass spectrometry, and recent advances have enabled quantifying thousands of proteins in single cells.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Protein quantification by mass spectrometry benefits from efficient sampling (counting) of many ions per protein compared to other methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Quantifications can be performed by label-free methods and by multiplexed methods, which use isotopic mass tags as labels.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Multiplexed methods can improve both quantitative accuracy and throughput.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Typically, stable (e.g. non-radioactive) heavier isotopes of carbon (13C) or nitrogen (15N) are incorporated into one sample while the other one is labeled with corresponding light isotopes (e.g.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The two samples are mixed before the analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Peptides derived from the different samples can be distinguished due to their mass difference.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The ratio of their peak intensities corresponds to the relative abundance ratio of the peptides (and proteins).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The first generation of methods for isotope labeling included SILAC (stable isotope labeling by amino acids in cell culture), trypsin-catalyzed 18O labeling, ICAT (isotope coded affinity tagging), and iTRAQ (isobaric tags for relative and absolute quantitation).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The more recent generation of multiplexing methods include tandem mass tags (TMT) for DDA data and mTRAQ for multiplexed DIA (plexDIA).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] "Semi-quantitative" mass spectrometry can be performed without labeling of samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Typically, this is done with MALDI analysis (in linear mode).
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] The peak intensity, or the peak area, from individual molecules (typically proteins) is here correlated to the amount of protein in the sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] However, the individual signal depends on the primary structure of the protein, on the complexity of the sample, and on the settings of the instrument.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Other types of "label-free" quantitative mass spectrometry, uses the spectral counts (or peptide counts) of digested proteins as a means for determining relative protein amounts.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Characteristics indicative of the 3-dimensional structure of proteins can be probed with mass spectrometry in various ways.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Comparing charge state distributions can give information about the structure of a protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] A wide variety of high charge states indicates disorder of the protein, whereas more compact, folded proteins result in lower charge states.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] By using chemical crosslinking to couple parts of the protein that are close in space, but far apart in sequence, information about the overall structure can be inferred.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] By following the exchange of amide protons with deuterium from the solvent, it is possible to probe the solvent accessibility of various parts of the protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Hydrogen-deuterium exchange mass spectrometry has been used to study proteins and their conformations for over 20 years.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] This type of protein structural analysis can be suitable for proteins that are challenging for other structural methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Another interesting avenue in protein structural studies is laser-induced covalent labeling.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In this technique, solvent-exposed sites of the protein are modified by hydroxyl radicals.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Its combination with rapid mixing has been used in protein folding studies.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] In what is now commonly referred to as proteogenomics, peptides identified with mass spectrometry are used for improving gene annotations (for example, gene start sites) and protein annotations.
[src:proteomics-bio/protein-mass-spectrometry] Parallel analysis of the genome and the proteome facilitates discovery of post-translational modifications and proteolytic events, especially when comparing multiple species.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteins are vital macromolecules of all living organisms, with many functions such as the formation of structural fibers of muscle tissue, enzymatic digestion of food, or synthesis and replication of DNA.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In addition, other kinds of proteins include antibodies that protect an organism from infection, and hormones that send important signals throughout the body.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteomics enables the identification of ever-increasing numbers of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This varies with time and distinct requirements, or stresses, that a cell or organism undergoes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The first studies of proteins that could be regarded as proteomics began in 1974, after the introduction of the two-dimensional gel and mapping of the proteins from the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] After genomics and transcriptomics, proteomics is the next step in the study of biological systems.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It is more complicated than genomics because an organism's genome is more or less constant, whereas proteomes differ from cell to cell and from time to time.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Distinct genes are expressed in different cell types, which means that even the basic set of proteins produced in a cell must be identified.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In the past this phenomenon was assessed by RNA analysis, which was found to lack correlation with protein content.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It is now known that mRNA is not always translated into protein, and the amount of protein produced for a given amount of mRNA depends on the gene it is transcribed from and on the cell's physiological state.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteomics confirms the presence of the protein and provides a direct measure of its quantity.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Not only does the translation from mRNA cause differences, but many proteins also are subjected to a wide variety of chemical modifications after translation.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The most common and widely studied post-translational modifications include phosphorylation and glycosylation.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Many of these post-translational modifications are critical to the protein's function.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] One such modification is phosphorylation, which happens to many enzymes and structural proteins in the process of cell signaling.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Because protein phosphorylation is one of the most studied protein modifications, many "proteomic" efforts are geared to determining the set of phosphorylated proteins in a particular cell or tissue-type under particular circumstances.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This alerts the scientist to the signaling pathways that may be active in that instance.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Ubiquitin is a small protein that may be affixed to certain protein substrates by enzymes called E3 ubiquitin ligases.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Determining which proteins are poly-ubiquitinated helps understand how protein pathways are regulated.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This is, therefore, an additional legitimate "proteomic" study.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Similarly, once a researcher determines which substrates are ubiquitinated by each ligase, determining the set of ligases expressed in a particular cell type is helpful.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In addition to phosphorylation and ubiquitination, proteins may be subjected to (among others) methylation, acetylation, glycosylation, oxidation, and nitrosylation.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Some proteins undergo all these modifications, often in time-dependent combinations.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This illustrates the potential complexity of studying protein structure and function.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A cell may make different sets of proteins at different times or under different conditions, for example during development, cellular differentiation, cell cycle, or carcinogenesis.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Further increasing proteome complexity, as mentioned, most proteins are able to undergo a wide range of post-translational modifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Therefore, a "proteomics" study may become complex very quickly, even if the topic of study is restricted.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In more ambitious settings, such as when a biomarker for a specific cancer subtype is sought, the proteomics scientist might elect to study multiple blood serum samples from multiple cancer patients to minimise confounding factors and account for experimental noise.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Thus, complicated experimental designs are sometimes necessary to account for the dynamic complexity of the proteome.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In proteomics, there are multiple methods to study proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Generally, proteins may be detected by using either antibodies (immunoassays), electrophoretic separation or mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Antibodies to particular proteins, or their modified forms, have been used in biochemistry and cell biology studies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These are among the most common tools used by molecular biologists today.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] There are several specific techniques and protocols that use antibodies for protein detection.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) has been used for decades to detect and quantitatively measure proteins in samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The western blot may be used for detection and quantification of individual proteins, where in an initial step, a complex protein mixture is separated using SDS-PAGE and then the protein of interest is identified using an antibody.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Modified proteins may be studied by developing an antibody specific to that modification.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For example, some antibodies only recognize certain proteins when they are tyrosine-phosphorylated, they are known as phospho-specific antibodies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Also, there are antibodies specific to other modifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These may be used to determine the set of proteins that have undergone the modification of interest.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Immunoassays can also be carried out using recombinantly generated immunoglobulin derivatives or synthetically designed protein scaffolds that are selected for high antigen specificity.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Such binders include single domain antibody fragments (Nanobodies), designed ankyrin repeat proteins (DARPins) and aptamers.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Disease detection at the molecular level is driving the emerging revolution of early diagnosis and treatment.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A challenge facing the field is that protein biomarkers for early diagnosis may be present in very low abundance.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The lower limit of detection with conventional immunoassay technology is the upper femtomolar range (10−13 M).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Digital immunoassay technology has improved detection sensitivity three logs, to the attomolar range (10−16 M).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This capability has the potential to open new advances in diagnostics and therapeutics, but such technologies have been relegated to manual procedures that are not well suited for efficient routine use.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] While protein detection with antibodies is still very common in molecular biology, other methods have been developed as well, that do not rely on an antibody.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These methods offer various advantages, for instance they often are able to determine the sequence of a protein or peptide, they may have higher throughput than antibody-based, and they sometimes can identify and quantify proteins for which no antibody exists.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] One of the earliest methods for protein analysis has been Edman degradation (introduced in 1967) where a single peptide is subjected to multiple steps of chemical degradation to resolve its sequence.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These early methods have mostly been supplanted by technologies that offer higher throughput.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] More recently implemented methods use mass spectrometry-based techniques, a development that was made possible by the discovery of "soft ionization" methods developed in the 1980s, such as matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI) and electrospray ionization (ESI).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These methods gave rise to the top-down and the bottom-up proteomics workflows where often additional separation is performed before analysis (see below).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For the analysis of complex biological samples, a reduction of sample complexity is required.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This may be performed off-line by one-dimensional or two-dimensional separation.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] More recently, on-line methods have been developed where individual peptides (in bottom-up proteomics approaches) are separated using reversed-phase chromatography and then, directly ionized using ESI; the direct coupling of separation and analysis explains the term "on-line" analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Several hybrid technologies use antibody-based purification of individual analytes and then perform mass spectrometric analysis for identification and quantification.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Examples of these methods are the MSIA (mass spectrometric immunoassay), developed by Randall Nelson in 1995, and the SISCAPA (Stable Isotope Standard Capture with Anti-Peptide Antibodies) method, introduced by Leigh Anderson in 2004.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Fluorescence two-dimensional differential gel electrophoresis (2-D DIGE) may be used to quantify variation in the 2-D DIGE process and establish statistically valid thresholds for assigning quantitative changes between samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Comparative proteomic analysis may reveal the role of proteins in complex biological systems, including reproduction.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For example, treatment with the insecticide triazophos causes an increase in the content of brown planthopper (*Nilaparvata lugens* (Stål)) male accessory gland proteins (Acps) that may be transferred to females via mating, causing an increase in fecundity (i.e. birth rate) of females.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] To identify changes in the types of accessory gland proteins (Acps) and reproductive proteins that mated female planthoppers received from male planthoppers, researchers conducted a comparative proteomic analysis of mated *N. lugens* females.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The results indicated that these proteins participate in the reproductive process of *N. lugens* adult females and males.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteome analysis of *Arabidopsis* peroxisomes has been established as the major unbiased approach for identifying new peroxisomal proteins on a large scale.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] There are many approaches to characterizing the human proteome, which is estimated to contain between 20,000 and 25,000 non-redundant proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The number of unique protein species likely will increase by between 50,000 and 500,000 due to RNA splicing and proteolysis events, and when post-translational modification also are considered, the total number of unique human proteins is estimated to range in the low millions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In addition, the first promising attempts to decipher the proteome of animal tumors have recently been reported.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This method was used as a functional method in *Macrobrachium rosenbergii* protein profiling.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteomics has steadily gained momentum over the past decade with the evolution of several approaches.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Few of these are new, and others build on traditional methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Mass spectrometry-based methods, affinity proteomics, and micro arrays are the most common technologies for large-scale study of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] There are two mass spectrometry-based methods currently used for protein profiling.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The more established and widespread method uses high resolution, two-dimensional electrophoresis to separate proteins from different samples in parallel, followed by selection and staining of differentially expressed proteins to be identified by mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Despite the advances in 2-DE and its maturity, it has its limits as well.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The central concern is the inability to resolve all the proteins within a sample, given their dramatic range in expression level and differing properties.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The combination of pore size, and protein charge, size and shape can greatly determine migration rate which leads to other complications.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The second quantitative approach uses stable isotope tags to differentially label proteins from two different complex mixtures.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Here, the proteins within a complex mixture are labeled isotopically first, and then digested to yield labeled peptides.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The labeled mixtures are then combined, the peptides separated by multidimensional liquid chromatography and analyzed by tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Isotope coded affinity tag (ICAT) reagents are the widely used isotope tags.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In this method, the cysteine residues of proteins get covalently attached to the ICAT reagent, thereby reducing the complexity of the mixtures omitting the non-cysteine residues.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Quantitative proteomics using stable isotopic tagging is an increasingly useful tool in modern development.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Firstly, chemical reactions have been used to introduce tags into specific sites or proteins for the purpose of probing specific protein functionalities.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The isolation of phosphorylated peptides has been achieved using isotopic labeling and selective chemistries to capture the fraction of protein among the complex mixture.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Secondly, the ICAT technology was used to differentiate between partially purified or purified macromolecular complexes such as large RNA polymerase II pre-initiation complex and the proteins complexed with yeast transcription factor.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Thirdly, ICAT labeling was recently combined with chromatin isolation to identify and quantify chromatin-associated proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Finally ICAT reagents are useful for proteomic profiling of cellular organelles and specific cellular fractions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Another quantitative approach is the accurate mass and time (AMT) tag approach developed by Richard D.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Smith and coworkers at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In this approach, increased throughput and sensitivity is achieved by avoiding the need for tandem mass spectrometry, and making use of precisely determined separation time information and highly accurate mass determinations for peptide and protein identifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Affinity proteomics uses antibodies or other affinity reagents (such as oligonucleotide-based aptamers) as protein-specific detection probes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Currently this method can interrogate several thousand proteins, typically from biofluids such as plasma, serum or cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A key differentiator for this technology is the ability to analyze hundreds or thousands of samples in a reasonable timeframe (a matter of days or weeks); mass spectrometry-based methods are not scalable to this level of sample throughput for proteomics analyses.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Balancing the use of mass spectrometers in proteomics and in medicine is the use of protein micro arrays.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The aim behind protein micro arrays is to print thousands of protein detecting features for the interrogation of biological samples.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Antibody arrays are an example in which a host of different antibodies are arrayed to detect their respective antigens from a sample of human blood.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Another approach is the arraying of multiple protein types for the study of properties like protein-DNA, protein-protein and protein-ligand interactions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Ideally, the functional proteomic arrays would contain the entire complement of the proteins of a given organism.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The first version of such arrays consisted of 5000 purified proteins from yeast deposited onto glass microscopic slides.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Despite the success of the first chip, it was a greater challenge for protein arrays to be implemented.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteins are inherently much more difficult to work with than DNA.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] They have a broad dynamic range, are less stable than DNA and their structure is difficult to preserve on glass slides, though they are essential for most assays.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The global ICAT technology has striking advantages over protein chip technologies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This is a promising and newer microarray application for the diagnosis, study and treatment of complex diseases such as cancer.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The technology merges laser capture microdissection (LCM) with micro array technology, to produce reverse-phase protein microarrays.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In this type of microarrays, the whole collection of protein themselves are immobilized with the intent of capturing various stages of disease within an individual patient.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] When used with LCM, reverse phase arrays can monitor the fluctuating state of proteome among different cell population within a small area of human tissue.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This is useful for profiling the status of cellular signaling molecules, among a cross-section of tissue that includes both normal and cancerous cells.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This approach is useful in monitoring the status of key factors in normal prostate epithelium and invasive prostate cancer tissues.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] LCM then dissects these tissue and protein lysates were arrayed onto nitrocellulose slides, which were probed with specific antibodies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This method can track all kinds of molecular events and can compare diseased and healthy tissues within the same patient enabling the development of treatment strategies and diagnosis.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The ability to acquire proteomics snapshots of neighboring cell populations, using reverse-phase microarrays in conjunction with LCM has a number of applications beyond the study of tumors.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The approach can provide insights into normal physiology and pathology of all the tissues and is invaluable for characterizing developmental processes and anomalies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Recent advancements in bioorthogonal chemistry have revealed applications in protein analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The extension of using organic molecules to observe their reaction with proteins reveals extensive methods to tag them.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Unnatural amino acids and various functional groups represent new growing technologies in proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Specific biomolecules that are capable of being metabolized in cells or tissues are inserted into proteins or glycans.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The molecule will have an affinity tag, modifying the protein allowing it to be detected.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Azidohomoalanine (AHA) utilizes this affinity tag via incorporation with Met-t-RNA synthetase to incorporate into proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This has allowed AHA to assist in determine the identity of newly synthesized proteins created in response to perturbations and to identify proteins secreted by cells.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Recent studies using ketones and aldehydes condensations show that they are best suited for in vitro or cell surface labeling.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] However, using ketones and aldehydes as bioorthogonal reporters revealed slow kinetics indicating that while effective for labeling, the concentration must be high.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Certain proteins can be detected via their reactivity to azide groups.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Non-proteinogenic amino acids can bear azide groups which react with phosphines in Staudinger ligations.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This reaction has already been used to label other biomolecules in living cells and animals.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The bioorthogonal field is expanding and is driving further applications within proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It is worthwhile noting the limitations and benefits.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Rapid reactions can create bioconjuctions and create high concentrations with low amounts of reactants.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Contrarily slow kinetic reactions like aldehyde and ketone condensation while effective require a high concentration making it cost inefficient.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] One major outcome of research on human genes and proteins has been the identification of potential new drugs for the treatment of disease.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This process relies on genome and proteome information to identify proteins associated with specific diseases, which can then be evaluated as therapeutic targets using computational approaches.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For example, when a protein is implicated in a disease, knowledge of its three-dimensional structure can guide the design of drugs that interfere with its function.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A molecule that fits into the active site of an enzyme but cannot be released can effectively inactivate the enzyme.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This principle underlies many modern drug-discovery strategies, which aim to identify compounds capable of modulating or inhibiting disease-relevant proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] As genetic differences among individuals are increasingly characterized, these approaches are expected to support the development of personalized medicines tailored to improve efficacy for individual patients.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A branch of proteomics known as chemoproteomics provides a broad set of tools and techniques for identifying and characterizing the protein targets of drugs, thereby supporting drug discovery and development efforts.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] CETSA measures drug-induced changes in protein thermal stability in intact cells or tissues and, when combined with proteomics, enables the unbiased identification and ranking of on- and off-targets, as well as supporting phenotypic hit mechanism-of-action studies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] PISA extends thermal-shift principles by integrating protein solubility changes across a temperature gradient, substantially increasing throughput and enabling multiplexed analysis of multiple compounds, concentrations, or time points.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This approach facilitates high-content target deconvolution and comparative mechanism-of-action profiling, including applications in low-input or automated workflows.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Interaction proteomics is the analysis of protein interactions from scales of binary interactions to proteome- or network-wide.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Most proteins function via protein–protein interactions, and one goal of interaction proteomics is to identify binary protein interactions, protein complexes, and interactomes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Several methods are available to probe protein–protein interactions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] While the most traditional method is yeast two-hybrid analysis, a powerful emerging method is affinity purification followed by protein mass spectrometry using tagged protein baits.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Other methods include surface plasmon resonance (SPR), protein microarrays, dual polarisation interferometry, microscale thermophoresis, kinetic exclusion assay, and experimental methods such as phage display and *in silico* computational methods.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Knowledge of protein-protein interactions is especially useful in regard to biological networks and systems biology, for example in cell signaling cascades and gene regulatory networks (GRNs, where knowledge of protein-DNA interactions is also informative).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteome-wide analysis of protein interactions, and integration of these interaction patterns into larger biological networks, is crucial towards understanding systems-level biology.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Expression proteomics includes the analysis of protein expression at a larger scale.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It helps identify main proteins in a particular sample, and those proteins differentially expressed in related samples—such as diseased vs. healthy tissue.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] If a protein is found only in a diseased sample then it can be a useful drug target or diagnostic marker.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Proteins with the same or similar expression profiles may also be functionally related.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] There are technologies such as 2D-PAGE and mass spectrometry that are used in expression proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Understanding the proteome, the structure and function of each protein and the complexities of protein–protein interactions are critical for developing the most effective diagnostic techniques and disease treatments in the future.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] An interesting use of proteomics is using specific protein biomarkers to diagnose disease.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A number of techniques allow to test for proteins produced during a particular disease, which helps to diagnose the disease quickly.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Techniques include western blot, immunohistochemical staining, enzyme linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) or mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Secretomics, a subfield of proteomics that studies secreted proteins and secretion pathways using proteomic approaches, has recently emerged as an important tool for the discovery of biomarkers of disease.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In proteogenomics, proteomic technologies such as mass spectrometry are used for improving gene annotations.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Parallel analysis of the genome and the proteome facilitates discovery of post-translational modifications and proteolytic events, especially when comparing multiple species (comparative proteogenomics).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Structural proteomics includes the analysis of protein structures at large-scale.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It compares protein structures and helps identify functions of newly discovered genes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The structural analysis also helps to understand that where drugs bind to proteins and also shows where proteins interact with each other.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This understanding is achieved using different technologies such as X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Much proteomics data is collected with the help of high throughput technologies such as mass spectrometry and microarray.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It would often take weeks or months to analyze the data and perform comparisons by hand.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For this reason, biologists and chemists are collaborating with computer scientists and mathematicians to create programs and data pipelines to computationally analyze the protein data.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Using bioinformatics techniques, researchers are capable of faster analysis and data storage.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A good place to find lists of current programs and databases is on the ExPASy bioinformatics resource portal.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The applications of bioinformatics-based proteomics include medicine, disease diagnosis, biomarker identification, and many more.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Mass spectrometry and microarray produce peptide fragmentation information but do not give identification of specific proteins present in the original sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Due to the lack of specific protein identification, past researchers were forced to decipher the peptide fragments themselves.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] However, there are currently programs available for protein identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These programs take the peptide sequences output from mass spectrometry and microarray and return information about matching or similar proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This is done through algorithms implemented by the program which perform alignments with proteins from known databases such as UniProt and PROSITE to predict what proteins are in the sample with a degree of certainty.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The biomolecular structure forms the 3D configuration of the protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Understanding the protein's structure aids in the identification of the protein's interactions and function.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It used to be that the 3D structure of proteins could only be determined using X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] As of 2017, Cryo-electron microscopy is a leading technique, solving difficulties with crystallization (in X-ray crystallography) and conformational ambiguity (in NMR); resolution was 2.2Å as of 2015.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Now, through bioinformatics, there are computer programs that can in some cases predict and model the structure of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] These programs use the chemical properties of amino acids and structural properties of known proteins to predict the 3D model of sample proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This also allows scientists to model protein interactions on a larger scale.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In addition, biomedical engineers are developing methods to factor in the flexibility of protein structures to make comparisons and predictions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Most programs available for protein analysis are not written for proteins that have undergone post-translational modifications.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Some programs will accept post-translational modifications to aid in protein identification but then ignore the modification during further protein analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It is important to account for these modifications since they can affect the protein's structure.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In turn, computational analysis of post-translational modifications has gained the attention of the scientific community.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The current post-translational modification programs are only predictive.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Chemists, biologists and computer scientists are working together to create and introduce new pipelines that allow for analysis of post-translational modifications that have been experimentally identified for their effect on the protein's structure and function.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] One example of the use of bioinformatics and the use of computational methods is the study of protein biomarkers.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Computational predictive models have shown that extensive and diverse feto-maternal protein trafficking occurs during pregnancy and can be readily detected non-invasively in maternal whole blood.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This computational approach circumvented a major limitation, the abundance of maternal proteins interfering with the detection of fetal proteins, to fetal proteomic analysis of maternal blood.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Computational models can use fetal gene transcripts previously identified in maternal whole blood to create a comprehensive proteomic network of the term neonate.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Such work shows that the fetal proteins detected in pregnant woman's blood originate from a diverse group of tissues and organs from the developing fetus.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The proteomic networks contain many biomarkers that are proxies for development and illustrate the potential clinical application of this technology as a way to monitor normal and abnormal fetal development.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] An information-theoretic framework has also been introduced for biomarker discovery, integrating biofluid and tissue information.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] This new approach takes advantage of functional synergy between certain biofluids and tissues with the potential for clinically significant findings not possible if tissues and biofluids were considered individually.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] By conceptualizing tissue-biofluid as information channels, significant biofluid proxies can be identified and then used for the guided development of clinical diagnostics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Candidate biomarkers are then predicted based on information transfer criteria across the tissue-biofluid channels.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Significant biofluid-tissue relationships can be used to prioritize clinical validation of biomarkers.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] A number of emerging concepts have the potential to improve the current features of proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Obtaining absolute quantification of proteins and monitoring post-translational modifications are the two tasks that impact the understanding of protein function in healthy and diseased cells.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Further, the throughput and sensitivity of proteomic assays, often measured as samples analyzed per day and depth of proteome coverage, respectively, have driven development of cutting-edge instrumentation and methodologies.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] For many cellular events, the protein concentrations do not change; rather, their function is modulated by post-translational modifications (PTM).
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Methods of monitoring PTM are an underdeveloped area in proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Selecting a particular subset of protein for analysis substantially reduces protein complexity, making it advantageous for diagnostic purposes where blood is the starting material.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Another important aspect of proteomics, yet not addressed, is that proteomics methods should focus on studying proteins in the context of the environment.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The increasing use of chemical cross-linkers, introduced into living cells to fix protein-protein, protein-DNA and other interactions, may ameliorate this problem partially.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The challenge is to identify suitable methods of preserving relevant interactions.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Another goal for studying proteins is development of more sophisticated methods to image proteins and other molecules in living cells and real-time.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Advances in quantitative proteomics would clearly enable more in-depth analysis of cellular systems.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Transcriptional and translational responses to these perturbations results in functional changes to the proteome implicated in response to the stimulus.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Therefore, describing and quantifying proteome-wide changes in protein abundance is crucial towards understanding biological phenomenon more holistically, on the level of the entire system.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] In this way, proteomics can be seen as complementary to genomics, transcriptomics, epigenomics, metabolomics, and other -omics approaches in integrative analyses attempting to define biological phenotypes more comprehensively.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] As an example, *The Cancer Proteome Atlas* provides quantitative protein expression data for ~200 proteins in over 4,000 tumor samples with matched transcriptomic and genomic data from The Cancer Genome Atlas.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Similar datasets in other cell types, tissue types, and species, particularly using deep shotgun mass spectrometry, will be an immensely important resource for research in fields like cancer biology, developmental and stem cell biology, medicine, and evolutionary biology.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Characterizing the human plasma proteome has become a major goal in the proteomics arena, but it is also the most challenging proteomes of all human tissues.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It contains immunoglobulin, cytokines, protein hormones, and secreted proteins indicative of infection on top of resident, hemostatic proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It also contains tissue leakage proteins due to the blood circulation through different tissues in the body.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The blood thus contains information on the physiological state of all tissues and, combined with its accessibility, makes the blood proteome invaluable for medical purposes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] It is thought that characterizing the proteome of blood plasma is a daunting challenge.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The depth of the plasma proteome encompasses a dynamic range of more than 1010 between the highest abundant protein (albumin) and the lowest (some cytokines) and is thought to be one of the main challenges for proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Temporal and spatial dynamics further complicate the study of human plasma proteome.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] The turnover of some proteins is quite faster than others and the protein content of an artery may substantially vary from that of a vein.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] All these differences make even the simplest proteomic task of cataloging the proteome seem out of reach.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] To tackle this problem, priorities need to be established.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Capturing the most meaningful subset of proteins among the entire proteome to generate a diagnostic tool is one such priority.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Secondly, since cancer is associated with enhanced glycosylation of proteins, methods that focus on this part of proteins will also be useful.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Again: multiparameter analysis best reveals a pathological state.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] As these technologies improve, the disease profiles should be continually related to respective gene expression changes.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Due to the above-mentioned problems plasma proteomics remained challenging.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] However, technological advancements and continuous developments seem to result in a revival of plasma proteomics as it was shown recently by a technology called plasma proteome profiling.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Due to such technologies researchers were able to investigate inflammation processes in mice, the heritability of plasma proteomes as well as to show the effect of such a common life style change like weight loss on the plasma proteome.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Numerous journals are dedicated to the field of proteomics and related areas.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Note that journals dealing with *proteins* are usually more focused on structure and function while *proteomics* journals are more focused on the large-scale analysis of whole proteomes or at least large sets of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/proteomics] Some relevant proteomics journals are listed below (with their publishers).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The molecules of a given sample are ionized and the first spectrometer (designated **MS1**) separates these ions by their mass-to-charge ratio (often given as **m/z** or m/Q).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ions of a particular m/z-ratio coming from MS1 are selected and then made to split into smaller fragment ions, e.g. by collision-induced dissociation, ion-molecule reaction, or photodissociation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These fragments are then introduced into the second mass spectrometer (**MS2**), which in turn separates the fragments by their m/z-ratio and detects them.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation step makes it possible to identify and separate ions that have very similar m/z-ratios in regular mass spectrometers.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Typical tandem mass spectrometry instrumentation setups include triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (QqQ), multi-sector mass spectrometer, ion trap, quadrupole–time of flight (Q-TOF), Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR), and hybrid mass spectrometers.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Triple quadrupole mass spectrometers use the first and third quadrupoles as mass filters.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When analytes pass the second quadrupole, the fragmentation proceeds through collision with gas.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Q-TOF mass spectrometers combine quadrupole and TOF instruments, which together enable fragmentation experiments that yield highly accurate mass quantitations for product ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is a method of mass spectrometry in which fragmented ion (*m*/*z*) ratios are determined through a time of flight measurement.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Hybrid mass spectrometers consist of more than two mass analyzers.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Multiple stages of mass analysis separation can be accomplished with individual mass spectrometer elements separated in space or using a single mass spectrometer with the MS steps separated in time.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For tandem mass spectrometry in space, the different elements are often noted in a shorthand, giving the type of mass selector used.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In tandem mass spectrometry *in space*, the separation elements are physically separated and distinct, although there is a physical connection between the elements to maintain high vacuum.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These elements can be sectors, transmission quadrupole, or time-of-flight.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When using multiple quadrupoles, they can act as both mass analyzers and collision chambers.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Common notation for mass analyzers is *Q* – quadrupole mass analyzer; *q* – radio frequency collision quadrupole; *TOF* – time-of-flight mass analyzer; *B* – magnetic sector, and *E* – electric sector.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The notation can be combined to indicate various hybrid instrument, for example *QqQ'* – triple quadrupole mass spectrometer; *QTOF* – quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer (also *QqTOF*); and *BEBE* – four-sector (reverse geometry) mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] By doing tandem mass spectrometry *in time*, the separation is accomplished with ions trapped in the same place, with multiple separation steps taking place over time.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A quadrupole ion trap or Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance instrument can be used for such an analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Trapping instruments can perform multiple steps of analysis, which is sometimes referred to as MS*n* (MS to the *n*).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often the number of steps, *n*, is not indicated, but occasionally the value is specified; for example MS3 indicates three stages of separation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem in time MS instruments do not use the modes described next, but typically collect all of the information from a precursor ion scan and a parent ion scan of the entire spectrum.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Each instrumental configuration utilizes a unique mode of mass identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When tandem MS is performed with an in space design, the instrument must operate in one of a variety of modes.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are a number of different tandem MS/MS experimental setups and each mode has its own applications and provides different information.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem MS in space uses the coupling of two instrument components which measure the same mass spectrum range but with a controlled fractionation between them in space, while tandem MS in time involves the use of an ion trap.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are four main scan experiments possible using MS/MS: precursor ion scan, product ion scan, neutral loss scan, and selected reaction monitoring.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For a precursor ion scan, the product ion is selected in the second mass analyzer, and the precursor masses are scanned in the first mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Note that precursor ion is synonymous with parent ion and product ion with daughter ion; however the use of these anthropomorphic terms is discouraged.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a product ion scan, a precursor ion is selected in the first stage, allowed to fragment and then all resultant masses are scanned in the second mass analyzer and detected in the detector that is positioned after the second mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This experiment is commonly performed to identify transitions used for quantification by tandem MS.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a neutral loss scan, the first mass analyzer scans all the masses.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The second mass analyzer also scans, but at a set offset from the first mass analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This offset corresponds to a neutral loss that is commonly observed for the class of compounds.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a constant-neutral-loss scan, all precursors that undergo the loss of a specified common neutral are monitored.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To obtain this information, both mass analyzers are scanned simultaneously, but with a mass offset that correlates with the mass of the specified neutral.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to the precursor-ion scan, this technique is also useful in the selective identification of closely related class of compounds in a mixture.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In selected reaction monitoring, both mass analyzers are set to a selected mass.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This mode is analogous to selected ion monitoring for MS experiments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A selective analysis mode, which can increase sensitivity.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation of gas-phase ions is essential to tandem mass spectrometry and occurs between different stages of mass analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are many methods used to fragment the ions and these can result in different types of fragmentation and thus different information about the structure and composition of the molecule.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often, the ionization process is sufficiently violent to leave the resulting ions with sufficient internal energy to fragment within the mass spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If the product ions persist in their non-equilibrium state for a moderate amount of time before auto-dissociation this process is called metastable fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Nozzle-skimmer fragmentation refers to the purposeful induction of in-source fragmentation by increasing the nozzle-skimmer potential on usually electrospray based instruments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although in-source fragmentation allows for fragmentation analysis, it is not technically tandem mass spectrometry unless metastable ions are mass analyzed or selected before auto-dissociation and a second stage of analysis is performed on the resulting fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation can be used in lieu of tandem mass spectrometry through the utilization of enhanced in-source fragmentation annotation (EISA) technology which generates fragmentation that directly matches tandem mass spectrometry data.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragments observed by EISA have higher signal intensity than traditional fragments which suffer losses in the collision cells of tandem mass spectrometers.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] EISA enables fragmentation data acquisition on MS1 mass analyzers such as time-of-flight and single quadrupole instruments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation is often used in addition to tandem mass spectrometry (with post-source fragmentation) to allow for two steps of fragmentation in a pseudo MS3-type of experiment.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Post-source fragmentation is most often what is being used in a tandem mass spectrometry experiment.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Energy can also be added to the ions, which are usually already vibrationally excited, through post-source collisions with neutral atoms or molecules, the absorption of radiation, or the transfer or capture of an electron by a multiply charged ion.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Collision-induced dissociation (CID), also called collisionally activated dissociation (CAD), involves the collision of an ion with a neutral atom or molecule in the gas phase and subsequent dissociation of the ion.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where the ion AB+ collides with the neutral species M and subsequently breaks apart.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The details of this process are described by collision theory.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Due to different instrumental configuration, two main different types of CID are possible: *(i)* beam-type (in which precursor ions are fragmented on-the-flight) and *(ii)* ion trap-type (in which precursor ions are first trapped, and then fragmented).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A third and more recent type of CID fragmentation is higher-energy collisional dissociation (HCD).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a CID technique specific to orbitrap mass spectrometers in which fragmentation takes place external to the ion trap, it happens in the HCD cell (in some instruments named "ion routing multipole").
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a trap-type fragmentation that has been shown to have beam-type characteristics.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Freely available large scale high resolution tandem mass spectrometry databases exist (e.g.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] METLIN with 960,000 molecular standards each with experimental CID MS/MS data), and are typically used to facilitate small molecule identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The energy released when an electron is transferred to or captured by a multiply charged ion can induce fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If an electron is added to a multiply charged positive ion, the Coulomb energy is liberated.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Adding an electron through an ion-ion reaction is called electron-transfer dissociation (ETD).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to electron-capture dissociation, ETD induces fragmentation of cations (e.g. peptides or proteins) by transferring electrons to them.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Syka and Jarrod Marto at the University of Virginia.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] ETD cleaves randomly along the peptide backbone (c and z ions) while side chains and modifications such as phosphorylation are left intact.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The technique only works well for higher charge state ions (z>2), however relative to collision-induced dissociation (CID), ETD is advantageous for the fragmentation of longer peptides or even entire proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This makes the technique important for top-down proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Much like ECD, ETD is effective for peptides with modifications such as phosphorylation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-transfer and higher-energy collision dissociation (EThcD) is a combination ETD and HCD where the peptide precursor is initially subjected to an ion/ion reaction with fluoranthene anions in a linear ion trap, which generates c- and z-ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the second step HCD all-ion fragmentation is applied to all ETD derived ions to generate b- and y- ions prior to final analysis in the orbitrap analyzer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method employs dual fragmentation to generate ion- and thus data-rich MS/MS spectra for peptide sequencing and PTM localization.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Following this transfer event, the electron-deficient anion undergoes internal rearrangement and fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is the ion/ion analogue of electron-detachment dissociation (EDD).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is compatible with fragmenting peptide and proteins along the backbone at the Cα-C bond.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The resulting fragments are usually a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-detachment dissociation (EDD) is a method for fragmenting anionic species in mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It serves as a negative counter mode to electron capture dissociation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Negatively charged ions are activated by irradiation with electrons of moderate kinetic energy.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The result is ejection of electrons from the parent ionic molecule, which causes dissociation via recombination.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Reaction between positively charged peptides and cationic reagents, also known as charge transfer dissociation (CTD), has recently been demonstrated as an alternative high-energy fragmentation pathway for low-charge state (1+ or 2+) peptides.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Initial reports are that CTD causes backbone Cα-C bond cleavage of peptides and provides a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where $h\nu$ represents the photon absorbed by the ion.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ultraviolet lasers can be used, but can lead to excessive fragmentation of biomolecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Infrared photons will heat the ions and cause dissociation if enough of them are absorbed.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This process is called infrared multiphoton dissociation (IRMPD) and is often accomplished with a carbon dioxide laser and an ion trapping mass spectrometer such as a FTMS.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Blackbody radiation can be used for photodissociation in a technique known as blackbody infrared radiative dissociation (BIRD).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the BIRD method, the entire mass spectrometer vacuum chamber is heated to create infrared light.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD uses this radiation to excite increasingly more energetic vibrations of the ions, until a bond breaks, creating fragments.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is similar to infrared multiphoton dissociation which also uses infrared light, but from a different source.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD is most often used with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] With surface-induced dissociation (SID), the fragmentation is a result of the collision of an ion with a surface under high vacuum.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Today, SID is used to fragment a wide range of ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Years ago, it was only common to use SID on lower mass, singly charged species because ionization methods and mass analyzer technologies weren't advanced enough to properly form, transmit, or characterize ions of high m/z.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Over time, self-assembled monolayer surfaces (SAMs) composed of CF3(CF2)10CH2CH2S on gold have been the most prominently used collision surfaces for SID in a tandem spectrometer.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SAMs have acted as the most desirable collision targets due to their characteristically large effective masses for the collision of incoming ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Additionally, these surfaces are composed of rigid fluorocarbon chains, which don't significantly dampen the energy of the projectile ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fluorocarbon chains are also beneficial because of their ability to resist facile electron transfer from the metal surface to the incoming ions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SID's ability to produce subcomplexes that remain stable and provide valuable information on connectivity is unmatched by any other dissociation technique.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Since the complexes produced from SID are stable and retain distribution of charge on the fragment, this produces a unique, spectra which the complex centers around a narrower m/z distribution.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID products and the energy at which they form are reflective of the strengths and topology of the complex.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The unique dissociation patterns help discover the Quaternary structure of the complex.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The symmetric charge distribution and dissociation dependence are unique to SID and make the spectra produced distinctive from any other dissociation technique.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID technique is also applicable to ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Three different methods for this technique include analyzing the characterization of topology, intersubunit connectivity, and the degree of unfolding for protein structure.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Analysis of protein structure unfolding is the most commonly used application of the SID technique.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For Ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS), SID is used for dissociation of the source activated precursors of three different types of protein complexes: C-reactive protein (CRP), transthyretin (TTR), and concanavalin A (Con A).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method is used to observe the unfolding degree for each of these complexes.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For this observation, SID showed the precursor ions' structures that exist before the collision with the surface.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] IM-MS utilizes the SID as a direct measure of the conformation for each proteins' subunit.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance are able to provide ultrahigh resolution and high mass accuracy to instruments that take mass measurements.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These features make FT-ICR mass spectrometers a useful tool for a wide variety of applications such as several dissociation experiments such as collision-induced dissociation (CID, electron transfer dissociation (ETD), and others.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In addition, surface-induced dissociation has been implemented with this instrument for the study of fundamental peptide fragmentation.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Specifically, SID has been applied to the study of energetics and the kinetics of gas-phase fragmentation within an ICR instrument.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This approach has been used to understand the gas-phase fragmentation of protonated peptides, odd-electron peptide ions, non-covalent ligand-peptide complexes, and ligated metal clusters.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Quantitative proteomics is used to determine the relative or absolute amount of proteins in a sample.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Several quantitative proteomics methods are based on tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] MS/MS has become a benchmark procedure for the structural elucidation of complex biomolecules.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] One method commonly used for quantitative proteomics is isobaric tag labeling.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Isobaric tag labeling enables simultaneous identification and quantification of proteins from multiple samples in a single analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To quantify proteins, peptides are labeled with chemical tags that have the same structure and nominal mass, but vary in the distribution of heavy isotopes in their structure.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These tags, commonly referred to as tandem mass tags, are designed so that the mass tag is cleaved at a specific linker region upon higher-energy collisional-induced dissociation (HCD) during tandem mass spectrometry yielding reporter ions of different masses.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Protein quantitation is accomplished by comparing the intensities of the reporter ions in the MS/MS spectra.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Two commercially available isobaric tags are iTRAQ and TMT reagents.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] An isobaric tag for relative and absolute quantitation (iTRAQ) is a reagent for tandem mass spectrometry that is used to determine the amount of proteins from different sources in a single experiment.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It uses stable isotope labeled molecules that can form a covalent bond with the N-terminus and side chain amines of proteins.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The iTRAQ reagents are used to label peptides from different samples that are pooled and analyzed by liquid chromatography and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation of the attached tag generates a low molecular mass reporter ion that can be used to relatively quantify the peptides and the proteins from which they originated.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A tandem mass tag (TMT) is an isobaric mass tag chemical label used for protein quantification and identification.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The tags contain four regions: mass reporter, cleavable linker, mass normalization, and protein reactive group.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] TMT reagents can be used to simultaneously analyze 2 to 11 different peptide samples prepared from cells, tissues or biological fluids.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Recent developments allow up to 16 and even 18 samples (16plex or 18plex respectively) to be analyzed.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The progress in data independent acquisition (DIA) enabled multiplexed quantitative proteomics with non-isobaric mass tags and a new method called plexDIA introduced in 2021.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This new approach increases the number of data points by parallelizing both samples and peptides, thus achieving multiplicative gains.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has the potential to continue scaling proteomic throughput with new mass tags and algorithms. plexDIA is applicable to both bulk and single-cell samples and is particularly powerful for single-cell proteomics.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can be used for protein sequencing.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When intact proteins are introduced to a mass analyzer, this is called "top-down proteomics" and when proteins are digested into smaller peptides and subsequently introduced into the mass spectrometer, this is called "bottom-up proteomics".
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Shotgun proteomics is a variant of bottom up proteomics in which proteins in a mixture are digested prior to separation and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can produce a peptide sequence tag that can be used to identify a peptide in a protein database.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation has been developed for indicating peptide fragments that arise from a tandem mass spectrum.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Peptide fragment ions are indicated by a, b, or c if the charge is retained on the N-terminus and by x, y or z if the charge is maintained on the C-terminus.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The subscript indicates the number of amino acid residues in the fragment.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Superscripts are sometimes used to indicate neutral losses in addition to the backbone fragmentation, * for loss of ammonia and ° for loss of water.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although peptide backbone cleavage is the most useful for sequencing and peptide identification other fragment ions may be observed under high energy dissociation conditions.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These include the side chain loss ions d, v, w and ammonium ions and additional sequence-specific fragment ions associated with particular amino acid residues.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Oligosaccharides may be sequenced using tandem mass spectrometry in a similar manner to peptide sequencing.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation generally occurs on either side of the glycosidic bond (b, c, y and z ions) but also under more energetic conditions through the sugar ring structure in a cross-ring cleavage (x ions).
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Again trailing subscripts are used to indicate position of the cleavage along the chain.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For cross ring cleavage ions the nature of the cross ring cleavage is indicated by preceding superscripts.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry has been applied to DNA and RNA sequencing.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation for gas-phase fragmentation of oligonucleotide ions has been proposed.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Newborn screening is the process of testing newborn babies for treatable genetic, endocrinologic, metabolic and hematologic diseases.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The development of tandem mass spectrometry screening in the early 1990s led to a large expansion of potentially detectable congenital metabolic diseases that affect blood levels of organic acids.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has been shown that tandem mass spectrometry data is highly consistent across instrument and manufacturer platforms including quadrupole time-of-flight (QTOF) and Q Exactive instrumentation, especially at 20 eV.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry cannot be applied for single-cell analyses as it is insensitive to analyze such small amounts of a cell.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These limitations are primarily due to a combination of inefficient ion production and ion losses within the instruments due to chemical noise sources of solvents.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry will be a useful tool for protein characterization, nucleoprotein complexes, and other biological structures.
[src:proteomics-bio/tandem-mass-spectrometry] However, some challenges left such as analyzing the characterization of the proteome quantitatively and qualitatively.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] 2-D electrophoresis begins with electrophoresis in the first dimension and then separates the molecules perpendicularly from the first to create an electropherogram in the second dimension.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] In electrophoresis in the first dimension, molecules are separated linearly according to their isoelectric point.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] In the second dimension, the molecules are then separated at 90 degrees from the first electropherogram according to molecular mass.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Since it is unlikely that two molecules will be similar in two distinct properties, molecules are more effectively separated in 2-D electrophoresis than in 1-D electrophoresis.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The two dimensions that proteins are separated into using this technique can be isoelectric point, protein complex mass in the native state, or protein mass.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The result of this is a gel with proteins spread out on its surface.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] These proteins can then be detected by a variety of means, but the most commonly used stains are silver and Coomassie brilliant blue staining.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] In the former case, a silver colloid is applied to the gel.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The silver binds to cysteine groups within the protein.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The silver is darkened by exposure to ultra-violet light.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The amount of silver can be related to the darkness, and therefore the amount of protein at a given location on the gel.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] This measurement can only give approximate amounts, but is adequate for most purposes.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Silver staining is 100x more sensitive than Coomassie brilliant blue with a 40-fold range of linearity.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Molecules other than proteins can be separated by 2D electrophoresis.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] In supercoiling assays, coiled DNA is separated in the first dimension and denatured by a DNA intercalator (such as ethidium bromide or the less carcinogenic chloroquine) in the second.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] This is comparable to the combination of native PAGE/SDS-PAGE in protein separation.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] A common technique is to use an Immobilized pH gradient (IPG) in the first dimension.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] This technique is referred to as **IPG-DALT**.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] The sample is first separated onto IPG gel (which is commercially available) then the gel is cut into slices for each sample which is then equilibrated in SDS-mercaptoethanol and applied to an SDS-PAGE gel for resolution in the second dimension.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Typically IPG-DALT is not used for quantification of proteins due to the loss of low molecular weight components during the transfer to the SDS-PAGE gel.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] In quantitative proteomics, these tools primarily analyze bio-markers by quantifying individual proteins, and showing the separation between one or more protein "spots" on a scanned image of a 2-DE gel.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Additionally, these tools match spots between gels of similar samples to show, for example, proteomic differences between early and advanced stages of an illness.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] While this technology is widely utilized, the intelligence has not been perfected.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] For example, some software may tend to agree on the quantification and analysis of well-defined well-separated protein spots, they deliver different results and analysis tendencies with less-defined less-separated spots.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Comparative studies have previously been published to guide researchers on the "best" software for their analysis.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Generated picking lists can be used for the automated in-gel digestion of protein spots, and subsequent identification of the proteins by mass spectrometry.
[src:proteomics-bio/two-dimensional-gel-electrophoresis] Mass spectrometry analysis can identify precise mass measurements along with the sequencing of peptides that range from 1000–4000 atomic mass units.
